<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SAS to Add Beijing-Copenhagen Flight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Scandinavian Airlines
System (SAS), one of Europe's major airlines, will introduce its
fifth flight between Beijing and Copenhagen, the gateway to
Europe, on September 20 this year.
</P>
<P>
SAS will fly from Beijing every Monday, Tuesday, Thursday,
Saturday, and Sunday, becoming the second largest European airline
operating from China in terms of the number of flights.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft, a Boeing-767, which holds about 200 passengers
and 14 tons of cargo, will leave Copenhagen every Friday at 3:50
p.m, and after nine hours of non-stop flight it will land at
the Beijing Capital International Airport early Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
After a short stop in Beijing, the aircraft will depart at 9:05
a.m Saturday with early afternoon arrival in Copenhagen, then head
for other European cities through SAS's extensive European network.
</P>
<P>
SAS is the national carrier of Denmark, Norway, and Sweden,
with its head office in Stockholm, Sweden and its main hub in
Copenhagen, Denmark.
</P>
<P>
"Tourism, trade, and cooperation between China and the
three Scandinavian countries (Denmark, Norway and Sweden), have
developed very positively over the past few years, and I have
every reason to believe that this development will continue in the
coming years, making it necessary to add flights," said Erik
Gulmann, general manager of SAS China.
</P>
<P>
The airline is also a member of the Star Alliance, the world's
largest and most comprehensive airline partner alliance. Other
members are Air Canada, Lufthansa, Thai Airways, and United
Airlines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
