<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France, Lebanon to Sign Major Financial Protocol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 10 (Xinhua) -- France and Lebanon will sign a
major financial protocol during the visit by Lebanese Prime
Minister Rafic Hariri here Thursday and Friday, said French
Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt today.
</P>
<P>
"In order to show all the importance he attaches to the
relations with Lebanon, (Prime Minister) Lionel Jospin has decided
to sign himself the financial protocol for 1997," said
Rummelhardt.
</P>
<P>
The Arabic daily al-Hayat said that the amount of the loan to
be offered by France to Lebanon is 250 million francs (40 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The loan will allow French enterprises to participate fully in
the reconstruction projects of Lebanon, especially in water
processing and provision projects.
</P>
<P>
About 100 French enterprises are investing in Lebanon in the
fields of telecommunications, electricity and banking
institutions.
</P>
<P>
About 60 French companies signed with their Lebanese
counterparts contracts amounting to half a billion U.S. dollars in
1996, according to Agence France-Presse.
</P>
<P>
The European Development Bank signed today in Beirut with the
Lebanese government an agreement on providing a 131 million ECU
(164 million U.S. dollar) loan to Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
