<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Hours On the Way to the 15th CPC National Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 10 (Xinhua) -- More than 60 delegates from
China's largest and wealthiest city of Shanghai today boarded a
plane headed for China's capital Beijing, where the 15th National
Congress of the Communist Party of China (CPC) is to be convened.
</P>
<P>
Excited and prepared for a grand event, the delegates,
representing the city's 1.17 million Party members and the 13
million population, had hardly taken their seats before heated
discussions began.
</P>
<P>
Delegate Zhu Jiping became a popular figure, constantly
approached by other delegates concerned about scientific
development in the city.
</P>
<P>
Zhu, along with colleagues in the municipal science and
technology committee, has come up with the basic idea for the
acceleration of the industrialization process of high technology
in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
"The output value from the hi-tech sector will take up over 20
percent of the city's total industrial output value by the year
2000, which is 5.2 percentage points higher than the present," Zhu
said.
</P>
<P>
General Manager of Shanghai Automobile Industrial Group, Chen
Xianglin echoed Zhu, pointing out that progress in science and
technology is the ultimate force needed to push his company
forward.
</P>
<P>
"We have set targets for the company," he said. "First, it is
to make 100 billion yuan by the end of this century. Second, it
will strive to rank itself among the world's top 500 companies in
terms of overall ability."
</P>
<P>
Delegates from state-owned enterprises sat in a group, spending
their hours on the place talking about reforms in the sector. They
voiced their confidence in the future of state businesses when
they said they were encouraged by Chinese President Jiang Zemin's
May 29 speech to the Party School of the CPC Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
A series of statistics listed by Guan Zhuangmin, Party
secretary of the Baoshan Steel and Steel Corporation, amazed the
group.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the century, the corporation will be able to
claim that it has spent only 22 years to catch up with what took
developed countries 55 years to achieve, he said.
</P>
<P>
"In my opinion, Party members in the corporation, who take up
24.2 percent of the total workforce, contributed the most with
their work styles, which in turn encouraged others to work harder."
</P>
<P>
"The Party organization and political advantages in state-owned
enterprises are the most valuable elements for revitalization,"
said Guan, who will present a related report to the congress.
</P>
<P>
"The congress marks a new beginning for the cause of socialism
in China," said Meng Jianzhu, deputy secretary of the Shanghai
Shanghai. "As long as we adhere to the basic routes and policies
mapped out during the congress, a rejuvenated China will
undoubtedly present itself."
</P>
<P>
Huang Ju, member of the Party Politburo of the CPC Central
Committee and Party secretary of the CPC Shanghai Municipal Party
Committee, and Xu Kuangdi, mayor of Shanghai, greeted the
delegates at their hotel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
