<HEADLINE> China Holds First Bamboo Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, September 10 (Xinhua) -- China's first Bamboo
Cultural Festival closed today in Anji County in east China's
Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
The three-day festival, sponsored jointly by the Ministry of
Forestry and the provincial government, has attracted many bamboo
experts, business people and farmers at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
China has more than 66 million mu (4.4 million hectares) of
bamboo, which can be divided into over 300 types and are grown in
the country's 16 provinces, especially Fujian, Jiangxi, Hunan and
Zhejiang.
</P>
<P>
China, called the "kingdom of bamboo," ranks first in the world
in types, planting areas and supply of bamboo.
</P>
<P>
Anji County, regarded as China's "hometown of bamboo," boasts
over 900,000 mu of bamboo, averaging two mu per person.
</P>
<P>
The county has a 600-plus-mu bamboo park with 300 species of
bamboo, the biggest in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Figures show that the county scores 1.2 billion yuan (144.6
million US dollars) in output value in bamboo-processing every
year, accounting for one tenth of the country's total. Anji's
1,200 bamboo processors turn out more than 2,000 types of products.
</P>
<P>
China has a 6000-plus-year history of using bamboo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
