<HEADLINE> Albright Urges PNA, Israel to Rebuild </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Israel and the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) must rebuild their confidence in order
to restore the troubled Middle East peace process, U.S. Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright said here today.
</P>
<P>
Albright told a press conference after holding talks with
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu that the Middle East
peace process has been stalled and the PNA and Israel have lost
mutual trust. The two sides need to restore a partnership which is
beneficial to peace and stability of this region, she said.
</P>
<P>
She urged the PNA to strengthen security cooperation with
Israel in fighting against terrorism and achieving peace of this
region.
</P>
<P>
"My message is very clear that the PNA must take action to root
out terrorism and its intrastructure and I will convey this
message to PNA Chairman Arafat when I meet him tomorrow," she
said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, she urged Israel to shape a better
environment for revitalizing the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Israel has the responsibility in shaping such an environment
which will guarantee the successes of the Middle East peace
process, she stressed.
</P>
<P>
The United States is the key player in this process and it will
live up to the expectations of the people of this region and help
them build a beautiful future, she said.
</P>
<P>
Answering the question whether the United State still wants
all parties to implement the Oslo Accords, Albright said the
United States believes that all aspects of the Accords must be
implemented.
</P>
<P>
"It is important also not to abandon the Interim Agreement,"
she added.
</P>
<P>
Under the Interim Agreement, Israel must complete its troop
redeployment in the West Bank by mid-1998 in three stages.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the same conference, Netanyahu stressed that the PNA
must take concrete action to fight against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Albright arrived here today for a three-day visit, her first to
the region as secretary of state, which will also take her to the
PNA controlled areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
