<HEADLINE> Tibetan Inmates Reduced Jail Term, Released on Parole </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- One hundred and thirty-two
prisoners today were granted court-ordered prison term reductions
or parole in the Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Judges from the regional Higher People's Court and the
Intermediate People's Court of Lhasa, the regional capital,
announced the adjudications in the Regional Prison in the northern
suburb of Lhasa.
</P>
<P>
A presiding judge from the regional court told Xinhua, "The
target of reforming prisoners is to help them repent and turn a
new leaf at the earliest possible time, and to become useful
members of society."
</P>
<P>
Those who have shown evidence of reform and have done good
deeds while in prison will be treated with tolerance, he added.
</P>
<P>
Ciwang, one of the inmates who was paroled, showed his
excitement for the ruling, saying, "The government has provided us
with good conditions for reform in the prison, though my criminal
activities had caused severe damage to society."
</P>
<P>
The man learned how to weave wool carpets during his
imprisonment. "I will make a living as a weaver and become a
law-abiding civilian," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ciren Lamu, a female prisoner who received a four-year sentence
for endangering state security, was granted a one-year cut in her
term. "I'm young and was hooked by others to
advocate 'Independence of Tibet'." she said. "Now I have come to
know I was wrong."
</P>
<P>
She continued: "I know very little about the history of
Tibet. The living conditions and food in the prison are very
good. I will continue to strengthen my reform here."
</P>
<P>
According to Losang Gelie, warden of the regional prison, local
judicial departments in Tibet have reformed criminals in line with
the law.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the prisoners have been taught professional skills
and other useful knowledge, so as to help them reform themselves,
he noted, adding that a number of prisoners will receive sentence
reductions every year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
