<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean C. Bank Urged to Rein in Money Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The National Merchant Bank,
Zimbabwe's largest black-owned financial institution, today said
the Central Bank should maintain tight reins on inflation in
light of recent indications of further money supply expansion.
</P>
<P>
Group Chairman Paddy Zhanda said high government expenditure
and a bloated budget deficit problem called for the need to
re-visit the regime of austere monetary measures.
</P>
<P>
''Due to high government expenditure and difficulties in
controlling the fiscal deficit, the Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe will
have to maintain a tight monetary policy in the short- to
medium-term to contain inflation,'' he said, referring to the
group's results for the six months to June 30 this year.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged current efforts by the monetary authorities to
keep inflation, noting, however, that the central bank should
adopt a responsive rediscount rate policy in order to pass on the
benefits of falling inflation to the productive sector.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on last month's decision by the World Bank to
resume balance of payments support for Zimbabwe's reform program,
Zhanda said the move would stimulate business activity and
bolster economic growth.
</P>
<P>
''It should be noted, however, that Zimprest (Zimbabwe program
for economic and social transformation) is still to be officially
launched,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
