<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Foreign Ministry Office Spokesman on Ship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 10 (Xinhua) -- It was announced here
tonight that the Chinese Embassy in Colombo is making further
efforts to look for the five missing crew men of the Chinese cargo
ship which was attacked and set ablaze in Sri Lanka Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman for the Office of the Commissioner of the Chinese
Foreign Ministry in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region,
Wu Hongbo, said tonight that it has been confirmed that one of the
five missing crew men is from Hong Kong and the four others are
from China's inland areas.
</P>
<P>
The rescued 27 crew men from the ship have been taken into a
hotel in Trincomalee, a port city in northeastern Sri Lanka, the
spokesman said, adding that diplomats of the Chinese Embassy in
Colombo had arrived at the city and called on them.
</P>
<P>
Wu said that Chinese Embassy officials had requested the Sri
Lankan Navy to continue to search for the missing Chinese sailors
and tow the cargo ship into Trincomalee Port, and had also asked
the Office of the International Committee of the Red Cross in
Colombo, capital of Sri Lanka, to approach the Tamil Tigers over
the whereabouts of the missing sailors.
</P>
<P>
When representatives of the ship owner, China Ocean Shipping
Company (HK), arrive in Sri Lanka, Chinese diplomats will consult
with them on how to help arrange the rescued crew men back to the
motherland as soon as possible, he said.
</P>
<P>
The 34,873-ton cargo vessel sailed out of Hong Kong waters two
weeks ago and was scheduled to dock at Trincomalee on Tuesday
before sailing to Rotterdam.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday morning, some 15 rebel boats carrying dozens of Tamil
Tiger fighters attacked the cargo ship. A few of the
rocket-propelled grenades fired by the Tamil Tiger rebels struck
the ship and the engine room caught fire and was completely
damaged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
