<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Plans New Road Safety Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 10 (Xinhua) -- A road safety program
code-named "arrive alive" was being planned, South African
Transport Minister Mac Maharaj said today.
</P>
<P>
The program was designed to reduce the road accident rate,
which is costing the country billions of Rand each year, Maharaj
said at a press conference in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
According to Maharaj, a total of 517,669 road accidents last
year had cost the country 11,918 billion Rand (2.5 billion U.S.
Dollars). A total of 9,609 fatalities had been recorded.
</P>
<P>
The proposed program would focus on law enforcement,
communication, and speedy and effective adjudication, as well as
professionalism in traffic control and technology concerned, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The program would concentrate law enforcement on speeding,
driving under the influence of alcohol, wearing of seat belts,
unsafe overtaking, ignoring traffic signals and driving lincensess.
</P>
<P>
Vehicles would also have their tyres, lights, brakes, and
steering inspected as well as being checked for over-loading.
</P>
<P>
Although he disliked setting targets for improvement because
of unknown factors such as increased traffic, Maharaj said the
intention was to decrease the number of accidents and fatalities
by five percent.
</P>
<P>
He also expected to see the number of drunk drivers involved
in accidents reduced from seven to two percent, and pedestrians
from 14 to seven percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
