<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Ramos Keeps People Guessing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Filipinos will have to
continue guessing their president's plan in the 1998 polls as
President Fidel Ramos reiterated today that he will make a
decision in November on whether to run for another term.
</P>
<P>
At his weekly press conference, Ramos evaded answering whether
he will run again in 1998, but stressed he will reveal his
decision in November when his ruling Lakas-NUCD party convenes its
national convention.
</P>
<P>
Ramos also failed to clarify a statement made by him last
Friday that he was "keeping his options open." Instead, he again
explained that his options included choosing a successor from his
party for the 1998 polls.
</P>
<P>
The statement had been interpreted by many as a hint that Ramos
will probably seek another term under an amended constitution, and
gave rise to wide anxieties among the opposition, the Catholic
Church and the business sector.
</P>
<P>
Stubbornly declining to elaborate his options, Ramos told
reporters that he had to keep his options secret till November in
order to keep his party united.
</P>
<P>
Otherwise, he said, the party, which has seven presidential
aspirants for the next presidency, will be fragmented and will
risk losing grip on power after the 1998 polls.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said he will select his successor in November under party
rules, but stopped short of specifying who -- one of the ruling
party's presidential contenders or himself -- will be chosen as
the successor.
</P>
<P>
Also today, the country's two prominent opponents of charter
change -- Manila Archbishop Jaime Cardinal Sin and former
president Corazon Aquino -- expressed doubt that Ramos will not
seek another term.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Sin said his doubt was based on his
conversation with Ramos at a dinner meeting Tuesday night.
According to Sin, Ramos gave no answer when the archbishop asked
him whether to run again if the charter-change drive succeeds.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Ramos also rejected the demands of Sin and
Aquino to make a statement that he opposes changes to the charter
and will not seek re-election, according to local media.
</P>
<P>
Both Sin and Aquino vowed to press ahead the September 21 rally
in central Manila to protest against the charter change drive,
which has been pushed hard by Ramos' supporters in the Supreme
Court and the Congress since last year.
</P>
<P>
Under the country's 1987 constitution, Ramos can only serve one
single six-year term, and must step down in June 1998 when his
term expires.
</P>
<P>
But Ramos' supporters have sought to change the constitution to
lift term limits of all elective government officials, including
Ramos.
</P>
<P>
Ramos' dubious stance on charter change and his term limit will
affect the economy as investors are concerned over political
stability in the country, economy analysts here warned, citing the
turmoil in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
The country's stock market rebounded sharply Tuesday, with its
main index surging 5.8 percent to close at 2228.85 points, one day
after Ramos declared that the 1998 polls will proceed as scheduled
and he will not proclaim martial law.
</P>
<P>
But today, the main index for the local bourse dropped 1.17
percent to close at 2212.77 points, due to reports that Ramos, at
his meeting with Sin, still insisted on "keeping his options
open." Analysts said investors' waning concerns over political
stability were revived by the reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mentally Handicapped Sterilized by Force in France: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 15,000 women diagnosed
as "mentally handicapped" by French institutions were reportedly
forced to submit to sterilization over the past 20 to 30 years,
a recent issue of a satirical daily called Charlie Hebdo reported.
</P>
<P>
This report has created a scandal since France denied
permitting forced sterilization to "improve human quality."
</P>
<P>
The report has been confirmed by Nicole Diederich, a researcher
at the National Institute of Health and Medical Research (INSERM),
who said the victims of this practice number in thousands in
France.
</P>
<P>
She said she once tried to warn the French government against
forced sterilizations, which she said were "until now hidden" by
the institutions engaged in the practice.
</P>
<P>
She said that in the Gironde region of southwest France, 35
percent of 260 women being treated for mental problems in some
unspecified psychiatrical and medical "establishments" were
sterilized.
</P>
<P>
The National Consultative Committee of Ethics (CCNE) of France
protested in 1996 against sterilization by force in France, Agence
France-Presse said.
</P>
<P>
Women who have a weak I.Q., who have failed in schools or have
difficulty in expressing their feelings could easily be subjected
to forced sterilization, said Diederich.
</P>
<P>
Other vague and highly disputable "mental weeknesses" shown by
women can also lead to their sterilization, often at the demand or
with the agreement of their families.
</P>
<P>
For example, a 40-year-old woman identified as "Michelle" was
forced to submit to sterilization at the age of 20 by her mother
because she was "annoying" and wanted to get married.
</P>
<P>
Charlie Hebdo said the figure of 15,000 only covers women of
the present generation and not those of previous generations or
immigrant women, many of whom were reportedly forced to have
sterilization operations in the 1960's.
</P>
<P>
In France, a total of 44,000 women with mental problems are now
being treated in hospitals, while an unspecified number are being
treated by psychiatric institutions or doctors and psychiatrists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
