<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Shipbuilding Industry Making Fast Progress (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 10 (Xinhua) -- China's shipbuilding industry
has developed remarkably in recent years to become the world's
third-largest manufacturer and sixth-highest recipient of orders
for new vessels.
</P>
<P>
Five percent of the ships built annually in the world come from
China, and Chinese-made ships are of equal quality to Korean-made
models and close to those manufactured in Japan, according to
official sources.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here attribute the achievements to the industry's
efforts in accelerating restructuring, granting enterprises the
right of self-decision on internal affairs, increasing
infrastructural investment, and giving priority to science and
technology.
</P>
<P>
According to sources, in 1982, the China State Shipbuilding
Corporation (CSSBC) was established on the basis of the former
Sixth Machine-Building Ministry, to become the country's first
ministry to drop its administrative functions and turn into a
market-oriented economic entity.
</P>
<P>
The two-decade reform, especially the new target set by the
14th National Congress of the Communist Party of China in 1992 to
build a socialist market economy, has pushed forward the
development of the country's shipbuilding industry.
</P>
<P>
The corporation experienced its fastest growth in the period of
1992-96, with its annual output value and tonnage of vessels built
reaching 17.9 billion yuan and 18.66 billion tons, increasing at
14 percent and 31 percent annually, respectively.
</P>
<P>
In the same period, the manufacturer also earned 6.2 billion
yuan from ship repairs, and manufactured 3.91 million kw of
diesel engines for ship use.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Shipbuilding Industry Making Fast Progress (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the meantime, China exported 3.15 billion US dollars worth
of vessels, up 29.3 percent annually. Ships are the sixth-largest
export item among the country's machinery and electrical products.
</P>
<P>
Between 1992-96, CSSBC invested nearly 10 billion yuan to build
and renovate its infrastructures so as to increase its
shipbuilding capacity by one million tons, dock-volume by 200,000
tons, and diesel engine manufacturing capacity by one million kw.
</P>
<P>
The company's shipbuilding capacity currently stands at 2.5
million tons, and is expected to exceed 3.8 million tons by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, China has drastically reduced its technological
gap with the advanced countries. The country is now capable of
manufacturing 4,000-TEUs container ships, 46,000-ton
chemicals-carrying vessels, 150,000-ton oil tanks, 52,000-ton
multipurpose vessels, and high-performance passenger
hydrofoils. CSSBC is also able to repair vessels with a capacity
of 300,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the rapidly growing shipbuilding industry has
contributed to the development of the country's defense sector.
The Chinese navy has been equipped with newly-developed warships
designed and manufactured by the corporation.
</P>
<P>
Officials with the company told Xinhua that it is the reform
policy that has boosted the fast growth of the industry, and
therefore new reform steps must be taken to realize a new round of
development in the industry.
</P>
<P>
CSSBC is now working to build up a modern enterprise system in
its subordinate firms. So far, it has one listed firm and several
enterprise groups.
</P>
<P>
According to CSSBC sources, the corporation plans to do more to
meet the needs of national economic development and the defense
sector, while largely increasing its exports.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the century, China is expected to rank among
advanced shipbuilding countries, and by 2010 is expected to become
a major global competitor in the industry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Farmers Urged to Prepare for Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Lands and
Agriculture Minister Kumbirai Kangai today urged farmers and the
rest of the population to brace for a possible drought during the
forthcoming rainy season.
</P>
<P>
He said the whole country should prepare to manage the looming
drought which has been directly linked to the El Nino phenomenon
and expected to be the worst in the history of the country.
</P>
<P>
''We have done preparations to adequately inform the farming
community and the general public to prepare themselves both
physically and mentally for possibly the worst drought in our
living memories,'' Kangai said.
</P>
<P>
He added, ''we cannot stop the looming drought but we
certainly can prepare and manage it because we cannot manage to
have our people queuing for mealie-meal as was the case with the
1991/92 drought. It happened because we had no information but
now we have it.''
</P>
<P>
The government, he said, was monitoring the situation and by
the second week of October the country would be certain which
direction to take.
</P>
<P>
He said the government was currently making adequate
preparations to avert a possible disaster.
</P>
<P>
''Our main worry is that of livestock, and we need to put in
place necessary measures so that we curtail the looming danger of
having our herd again depleted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister added, ''we really have to be careful, but in
terms of food we really need not worry much as we have a huge
wheat and maize crop coming. But for all we know the El Nino may
even disappear much to our benefit.''
</P>
<P>
The El Nino, which occurs every three or four years, is the
warming of sea waters in the Pacific Ocean, weakening rain clouds
and unleashing natural disasters such as droughts and floods.
</P>
<P>
Experts expect the phenomenon, which intensified in June this
year, to get worse. Researchers in southern Africa said El Nino
is responsible for only five percent of the droughts in the
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Old Chinese Revolutionary Base Better Off These Days (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAN, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Li Yanping, a young farmer in
Yan'an, in China's Shannxi province in the North, earned 10,000
yuan (1,200 US dollars) last year from his six hectares of apple
trees.
</P>
<P>
Although he and his three other family members live in a cave
dwelling, it has a brick face and is practically identical to any
modern Chinese home, with its modern beds, sofa, color TV, and
refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
But, the portraits of Chairman Mao and Deng Xiaoping in a
prominent place on a wall of the livingroom remind the visitor
that this was once a Chinese revolutionary base.
</P>
<P>
"Chairman Mao liberated us poor people from the oppressive
landlords and Deng Xiaoping and his opening-up policies have put
us on the road to prosperity," said Li's father, a former head of
Miaogou village here.
</P>
<P>
The old man explains that the barren hills around the village
could hardly put enough food on the table of farmers here only ten
years ago. But they've now been changed to orchards thanks to rural
reforms that allowed peasants to get away from the traditional way
of farming and to work in their own interest.
</P>
<P>
Last year, per-capita income in Miaogou village was 5,000 yuan,
well above the national average. And the small village is
indicative of changes that have taken place in Yanan.
</P>
<P>
From 1936 to 1948, it was where the central committee of the
Communist Party had its headquarters. Chairman Mao lived and
worked there. And while it became a symbol of the successful
Chinese revolution, it unfortunately also became synonymous with
poverty after libration in 1949. The ever worsening soil erosion
deprived the local people of their basic means of living.
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhou Enlai was said to have shed tears when he heard
that many of the locals still had nothing but chaff and wild
plants to eat for half the year when he revisited the place in
1973.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Old Chinese Revolutionary Base Better of These Days  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The late Premier's desire to feed the people who had supported
the revolution was finally put into action in the 1980s when the
central government increased financial assistance to the
poverty-stricken area.
</P>
<P>
From 1985 to 1996, the central and local government spent more
than 200 million yuan on farmland so that each household could
grow its own grain. The local government also sold the sterile
hillside land to farmers at a very low price and encouraged them
to plant trees and orchards.
</P>
<P>
These measures helped raise the forest coverage in Yanan from
14 percent a decade ago to 43 percent, and last year's grain
harvest was a record high at 500 kg for each of the 1.9 million
rural people. Per capita income exceeded 1,000 yuan for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
The 10,000 hectares of orchards there are expected to produce
1.5 billion kg of fruit a year by the year 2000, which will help
raise per capita incomes to around 2,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
But what really makes the old revolutionary base different is
its petroleum oil business. Crude oil production is expected to
reach 2.5 million tons this year, 70 times the annual output in
1977, and the industry will have pre-tax profits of over a billion
yuan this year.
</P>
<P>
Today, Yan'an has the look of a modern city with its tall
buildings, beauty parlours, libraries, public swimming-pools,
children's parks, and other facilities.
</P>
<P>
Per-capita living space in the urban area is eight sq.m. and
there are 22 phones per 100 people, and 3,000 people with their
mobile phones that can reach other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
Gone are the images of local yokels with a red-rag belt tied
around the waist of a black cotton-padded jacket and a white towel
wrapped around their forehead - but that revolutionary legacy of
the Chinese past is not gone.
</P>
<P>
There are about 400 old revolutionary sites that are well
preserved and can be seen by the growing number of tourists. Red
Army veterans have been invited to speak to the younger
generations about the experience.
</P>
<P>
"My schedule is as tight as it ever was," said 76-year-old
veteran Zhang Qingyi who has addressed more than 40 gatherings
this year alone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Receive Japanese Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe is among five
African states selected by Japan for consistent economic support
in the next five years as Tokyo cuts back on aid to many
developing countries because of corruption and instability.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe News Agency reported today that President of the
Society for International Development of Japan Ryokichi Hirono
told a Zimbabwe journalist attending a fellowship program in
Tokyo that Kenya, Uganda, Tanzania, Ghana and Zimbabwe had been
selected on an experimental basis beginning this year.
</P>
<P>
''We selected countries that were politically stable,
perceived to be even remotely interested in development and
seemed to have potential,'' said Hirono, who is also
international aid advisor to Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto.
</P>
<P>
Projects were expected to focus on increasing food production,
broadening education, promoting a good economic climate and
training civil servants.
</P>
<P>
The Japaneseo government has cut its spending in government
departments and foreign aid by 10 percent due to an economic
downturn which has affected most east Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
Half of Japanese foreign aid is directed to Southeast Asia,
with Africa receiving 15 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
