<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Members Urged to Ensure Women's Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- A senior Zambian official
today urged the members of the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) to ensure that the status of women is enhanced,
reported the official Zambia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
This appeal was made by Minister of Foreign Affairs Lawrence
Shimba while speaking at the opening of a three-day international
conference for women and children in the sub-region in the
capital here.
</P>
<P>
Women's status should be enhanced so that they can participate
in making economic decisions for their countries, said Shimba,
stressing that women have a "vital" role to play in the economic
development of their countries.
</P>
<P>
He added that the economic policies and structural adjustment
programs of the SADC countries in the region should be formulated
and monitored in a "gender sensitive" way so that women can
participate effectively in their implementation.
</P>
<P>
ZANA quoted the minister as lamenting that despite the efforts
that have been made by various non-governmental organizations,
women empowerment has continued to be blocked by various
obstacles in the region.
</P>
<P>
Shimba placed emphasis on the need for the establishment of
institutions aimed at encouraging women to be elected to public
office.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the world and international organizations to
address the issue of the girl child.
</P>
<P>
Girls have continued to be restricted to traditional areas of
education in various parts of the world, making them unable to
contribute effectively to the future development of their nation,
said the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Shimba's remarks accorded with the spirit of the "Declaration
on Gender and Development" signed by the SADC leaders at a summit
meeting last Monday in Blantyre, Malawi.
</P>
<P>
The members of the SADC, which are striving for regional
economic integration, pledged to reach the target that 30 percent
of the women in the region will be empowered in political and
decision-making structures by the year 2005. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
