<HEADLINE> Iraq Preparing for Opening Trade Route With Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Iraq is preparing actively
for the opening of Al Waleed along the Iraqi-Syrian border as a
new trade route to facilitate the flow of foodstuffs and goods
from Syria, an Iraqi official has said.
</P>
<P>
Today's Iraqi daily "Al Thawra" quoted Iraqi Transport Under
Secretary Sabri Kadie as saying the opening up of the trading
route is in line with the oil-for-food accord signed between Iraq
and the United Nations in May last year.
</P>
<P>
The accord, which went into effect last December, allows Iraq
to sell 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil within six months to
purchase foodstuffs and medicine to alleviate the suffering of the
Iraqi people due to the embargo imposed against Iraq since its
1990 invasion of Kuwait. The accord was renewed last June.
</P>
<P>
Kadie pointed out that all necessary measures and arrangements
have been taken to set in motion the land transport fleets that
would carry goods, commodities and passengers between Syria and
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, he said, practical steps will be taken to facilitate
the flow of the transport fleet and to expedite the transport of
goods.
</P>
<P>
He further stated that private offices of the transport and
communication companies were opened and that efforts are being
exerted to repair the railway lines.
</P>
<P>
Iraq recently concluded contracts to the tune of 50 million
U.S. dollars with Syrian traders and businessmen.
</P>
<P>
The first consignment of 50,000 tonnes of sugar imported from
France will soon reach the Syrian port of Tartous, and will be
taken by land to Iraq through the Tanaf route which was opened to
goods and businessmen last June.
</P>
<P>
Iraq and Syria began the exchange of economic and trade
delegations in May. Meanwhile, officials of the two sides are
anticipating diplomatic rapprochement between the two countries for
the first time since the rupture of diplomatic relations 17 years
ago, when the war between Iran and Iraq broke out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
