<HEADLINE> Russia Concerned About Middle East Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Russia is concerned about the
recent developments in the Middle East and will make every effort
to promote the peace process in the region, President Boris
Yeltsin's press secretary Sergei Yastrzhembsky said today.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at a press conference held at a Moscow
international press club.
</P>
<P>
A series of terrorist attacks weeks ago have imperiled the
Middle East peace process and worsened relations among the
concerned countries, Yastrzhembsky said.
</P>
<P>
Russia, as a power actively engaged in the peace process and
having its own interests in the region, has every reason to be
concerned about the situation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Russia will do its best to keep the peace process on track, he
said.
</P>
<P>
On Russian-American relations, Yastrzhembsky said that he does
not think the United States is pursuing an anti-Russia policy. On
the contrary, the two countries are developing a mature
partnership, he said.
</P>
<P>
President Yeltsin and Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto
will hold informal meeting on November 1-2 in the eastern Russian
city of Krasnoyarsk, he said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will help promote Russian-Japanese relations,
enhance cooperation in trade, investment and other areas between
the two countries, he added. 
</P>
