<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Calls for Stronger Partnerships Between UN, NGOs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 10 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan today called for stronger partnerships between the
United Nations and the Non-Government Organizations (NGO).
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening session of the 50th annual NGO
Conference, the UN Chief said, "In 1947, the Member States of the
United nations were virtually the sole actors in the international
process, Non-government organizations were seen as supporters and
allies of the United Nations. They were important in a relatively
modest way. They were seen as mobilizers of public opinion in
support of the unique goals and values of the Charter of the
United Nations."
</P>
<P>
"Today, the relationship has been transformed. As the title of
this Conference recognizes, the relationship is a partnership.
Non-government organizations are now seen as essential partners
of the United Nations, not only in mobilizing public opinion,
but also in the process of deliberation and policy formulation,
and even more important in the execution of policies in work on
the ground," stressed Annan.
</P>
<P>
He said, "In a whole variety of ways, the NGOs have become
indispensable partners of the United Nations. NGOs are often
there on the ground before the international community gives
the UN the mandate to act. NGO information, guidance and
inspiration can be crucial to us at the United Nations."
</P>
<P>
"NGOs are particularly crucial in preventive diplomacy, in
humanitarian work in development and in human rights. The
relationship is complementary. Each contributes something
unique, producing a result that is greater than the sum of its
parts," Annan added.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general said, "The new partnership is more than
ever necessary. The world faces a daunting agenda of global
challenges. The relationship is vital because we face new enemies,
including drug-traffickers, money-launderers, gun-runners,
exploiters of young people for prostitution and currency
fraudsters. To combat them, international civil society must
mobilize. That is why Member States, governmental and
inter-governmental bodies, and non-governmental organizations work
together in partnership."
</P>
<P>
Annan proposed to target the year 2000 for the completion of
the task of launching a new and strong relationship between the
United Nations and the NGO community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Inflation Rate Rises to Two-Year High in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Britain's headline inflation
rose to a two-year high last month due to steep rises in mortgage
interest payments and the cost of summer holidays, according to
official figures released today.
</P>
<P>
The Office for National Statistics (ONS) said that retail
prices rose 0.6 percent last month, taking the annual inflation
rate from 3.3 percent in July to 3.5 percent in August, the
highest level since September 1995.
</P>
<P>
However, the underlying inflation rate, which excludes mortgage
interest payments, fell from 3.0 percent to 2.8 percent, although
it still remains above the government target figure of 2.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
The ONS said that the main reason for the rise in the headline
inflation rate was a further increase in mortgage rates as banks
and building societies responded to July's quarter-point rise in
base rates.
</P>
<P>
Other influences were rises in te cost of clothing and
footwear, foreign holidays and big ticket household items such as
televisions, washing machines and stereo equipment following the
summer sales.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the main cause of the decline in underlying
inflation was an unexpected drop in the price of seasonal foods,
the ONS said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believed that the figures will not affect the Bank of
England's Monetary Policy Committee, holding its monthly meeting
Wednesday and Friday. It is not expected to raise interest rates,
at least for now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
