<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greenpeace Protests EU Decision on GE Maize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The environmentalist group
Greenpeace today protested against a decision by the European
Union on repealing bans of genetically engineered maize (GE
maize).
</P>
<P>
The EU's executive agency, the European Commission, announced
earlier in the day its decision for Austria, Italy and Luxembourg
to lift bans on usage and sales of GE maize in their countries.
</P>
<P>
Greenpeace spokesperson Isabelle Meister said that despite
increasing scientific evidence of the dangers of GE plants, the
European Commission continued to allow its environmental policies
to be influenced by U.S. trade pressure.
</P>
<P>
This year's harvest of GE maize and soya has just started in
the United States and imports are expected to arrive in Europe
soon. Last year, 13 EU member states opposed the introduction of
GE maize from the U.S. while Austria and Luxembourg imposed a
national ban this February on U.S. GE maize. Their move was
followed by Italy.
</P>
<P>
In a press release, the European Commission said that it has
taken the decision after carefully considering the question of
monitoring insect resistance to Bt, a gene contained in the maize.
</P>
<P>
The gene has the effect of a low dose of antibiotic and the
plant is therefore less vulnerable to insects. The risk, however,
is that continued but low doses of this antibiotic develops a
resistance in insects that could cause problems later on, the EU
press release said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the decision-making has taken into consideration
the opinions of the EU scientific committees on food, for animal
nutrition and on pesticides.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the Greenpeace spokesperson blamed the EU decision for
inadequate tests and information. She quoted a recent issue of the
Swiss journal Facts as reporting that two out of three beneficial
predator insect larvae died when they were fed with European corn
borer which had eaten the GE maize. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
