<HEADLINE> UAE to Ratify Draft Law on Money Laundering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates
(UAE) will soon ratify a draft law on money laundering, which
will give the country's Authorities much more power to
investigate funds of drug suspects, a senior narcotics official
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Matar al Muheiri, head of the Narcotics Section at the General
Directorate of Abu Dhabi Police told reporters that the UAE will
ratify a draft law on money laundering within a few months and
"this would give the authorities greater access to bank accounts
and allow them to freeze the funds of drug suspects."
</P>
<P>
Under the draft law, money laundering will be addressed in
the context of organized crime which has become an international
phenomenon, said the official who attended the 11th meeting of
directors of anti-narcotics departments in the Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) which concluded here today.
</P>
<P>
The draft law was published a month ago. Shortly after
the publication, the UAE Central Bank froze bank accounts of
eight people suspected of involvement in drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
The draft law, which is to be ratified by the UAE Federal
Cabinet, follows a surge in narcotic trafficking by
international gangs in the Gulf country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
