<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Mandela Denies Abduction, Murder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 10 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela said he had not arranged the abduction and
imprisonment in Zambia of a witness in the kidnaping trial of
his former wife Winnie Madikizela-Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Mandela made the remarks in a statement issued by his office
in Cape Town on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
He was reacting to sensational allegations in the book written
by British journalist Fred Bridgland, based on interviews with
the witness, Katiza Cebekhulu and, among others, former Zambian
President Kenneth Kaunda.
</P>
<P>
The book, entitled Katiza's Journey, was launched in Cape Town
yesterday by former British Conservative Party parliament member
Emma Nicholson, who has sheltered Cebekhulu and championed his
cause since she discovered him in a Zambian jail in 1991.
</P>
<P>
According to the book, Kaunda implicated Mandela in
Cebekhulu's 1991 abduction and imprisonment without trial in
Zambia.
</P>
<P>
However, Mandela said in his statement that he did not arrange
for Cebekhulu to be taken out of South Africa or to be
incarcerated in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Mandela also denied having met Cebekhulu when he visited
Zambia in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Cebekhulu, before his disappearance, was among Winnie
Madikizela- Mandela's co-accused in a kidnapping and murder
trial, in which Winnie was found guilty and was later fined
15,000 Rands by an appeal court.
</P>
<P>
The book also claimed that Winnie was directly involved in the
murder of black activist Stompie and others in Soweto in 1980's.
</P>
<P>
The book describes how Nicholson, with the help of Kaunda's
successor President Frederick Chiluba, managed to trace the
missing Cebekhulu to a central Lusaka jail in 1991.
</P>
<P>
According to Zambian government's records, Cebekhulu's
abduction from South Africa indicated that Kaunda himself
believed Mandela might "have been the mastermind", claimed the
book.
</P>
<P>
Nicholson told a press conference in Cape Town yesterday that
she had been blocked on several occasions by senior South African
government officials and of the African National Congress (ANC)
from raising the matter.
</P>
<P>
Winnie, who is president of ANC National Women's League and
parliament member, told a press conference last night that all
the accusations were "cruel and depraved".
</P>
<P>
Referring to the allegations that Winnie was directly
responsible for several murders, Mandela said in his statement
that the Truth and Reconciliation Commission is currently
investigating the cases.
</P>
<P>
He said he fully supported the process initiated by the
Commission's amnesty sub-committee to establish the truth of the
allegations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
