postponement would be totally unacceptable," said the communique.
It claimed that the international community has undertaken a
tremendous effort to ensure that the elections can take place
under free and fair conditions.
</P>
<P>
"Threats of boycotts are unacceptable and must be met by a firm
reaction of the international community, especially the
signatories of the Dayton peace agreement," it added.
</P>
<P>
The European Union and the United States demand that all
threats of boycotts be dropped and that all Bosnians be encouraged
to fully exercise their rights to elect local leaders.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation union and the U.S. called on Croatia and the
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia to use their influence to prevent
boycotts of the municipal elections.
</P>
<P>
The communique warned that actions such as the illegal attempts
by the Pale SDS to intimidate and threaten the legitimate
leadership of the Republika Srpska under the guise of an election
rally will not be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
A total of 2,500 international observers will be present to
monitor the municipal elections slated for September 13 and 14
while the NATO-led Stabilization Force (SFOR) has been reinforced
to 39,000 troops and has been equipped with special policing
tools such as batons, shields, tear gases and non-lethal grenades
in case of evil-intended unrests prior to and during the
elections. 
