<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Sets Guideline for Tallow Production Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The European Union has set
out a guideline for the production process of tallow to lower the
risk of mad cow disease to as near to zero as possible.
</P>
<P>
Today's issue of the European Report, an official publication
of the European Union, said that the multidisciplinary scientific
committee and the scientific steering committee under the European
Commission have held a joint meeting to clarify the mad cow
disease risk status of tallow early this month.
</P>
<P>
The joint meeting advised that the risk of mad cow disease
infection presented by tallow is reduced to an acceptable level if
it is produced under three conditions.
</P>
<P>
The raw material is treated at a temperature of 133 degrees
Celsius at 3 bar pressure for at least 20 minutes prior to
rendering; the skull, brain, eyes, spinal cord and tonsils of
cattle are removed from the raw material prior to rendering.
</P>
<P>
Infectivity of the raw material can also be minimized by
sourcing it from regions or herds that are certified as mad cow
disease free.
</P>
<P>
Tallow is a fatty substance widely used as a raw material in
the pharmaceuticals industry and also for making candles, soap and
machinery grease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
