<HEADLINE> Iranian President Urges to Prevent Tensions in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami said here today that Iran is doing its best to prevent
tensions in the Persian Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with visiting Omani Minister of State for Foreign
Affairs Yousef Ben-Alawi, Khatami described the tension as
"detrimental to Persian Gulf's peace and security."
</P>
<P>
However, the 54-year-old president did not elaborate what
kind of tension in the region or where the source of tension
comes from.
</P>
<P>
But, observers noted that what the Iranian president means is
the tension caused by the United States, which deploys the Fifth
Fleet with a total of 20,000 forces in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Khatami stressed that closer cooperation among the regional
countries can lead to peace and tranquility in the region.
</P>
<P>
He lauded Oman's role in creating understanding among the
regional countries and highlighted the significance of regional
cooperation as the focus of Iran's foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
The Omani minister delivered a message of friendship from
Omani head of state Sultan Qaboos Bin-Said. He stressed his
country's resolve to further expand its ties with Iran.
</P>
<P>
But both sides did not reveal the content of the written
message.
</P>
<P>
The Omani state minister, who arrived here Tuesday and left
today, said Oman believes that friendly relations among the
regional countries can help achieve peace and security in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi who saw
off the Omani minister at the airport, described Tehran-Muscat
relations as friendly.
</P>
<P>
The discussions held between Iranian and Omani officials have
been very constructive, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
