<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women's Role in Politics Urged at World MP Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Parliamentarians around the
world meeting here today called for the establishment of
partnership between men and women to achieve full democracy in its
real sense.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the 98th Inter-Parliamentary Union (IPU)
Conference, Ahmed Faghi Sorour, president of the
Inter-Parliamentary Council, stressed women's role in promoting
democracy and human development.
</P>
<P>
He was addressing a meeting on women's role in politics opened
here today and attended by over 100 women parliamentarians from
the world.
</P>
<P>
"Men and women share responsibility in advancing social
development and human progress. There is no better way to fulfil
true democracy than forming partnership between them in politics,"
said Sorour, who doubles as the speaker speaker of the Egyptian
People's Assembly.
</P>
<P>
"Without woman, (there is) only partial democracy," he added.
</P>
<P>
The top Egyptian legislator said the IPU has been a strong
advocate of partnership between men and women in politics and
equal participation in decision-making.
</P>
<P>
About 1,600 parliamentarians is expected to participate in the
biannual event slated for September 11-16. The 138-member IPU was
formed in 1889 to promote personal contact of mps to the end of
developing representation and promoting cooperation between the
institutions.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting focused on the impact of armed conflicts on
women and children and Women's access to parliament.
</P>
<P>
Reports tabled at the meeting called for the recognition of the
fact that democracy is incomplete if without the participation of
women in making political decisions.
</P>
<P>
In her inaugural speech at the meeting, Suzane Mubarak, first
lady of Egypt, strongly denounced discrimination against women in
all walks of life and called for their empowerment to political
rights.
</P>
<P>
"There is no 100 percent equality anywhere in the world but we
should remember the balance of development is the key," she said.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics available at the meeting, women in
North Nodic countries have the highest representation (36.4
percent) in national parliaments, with Sweden taking the lead with
40.4 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
