<HEADLINE> Cyprus Proposes Turkish Cypriots Participate in EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government has
proposed that the Turkish Cypriots participate in its accession
talks with the European Union (EU) as part of the Cyprus
Republic's official delegation, government spokesman Manolis
Christofides announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Christofides said at a press briefing that the proposal was not
rejected by the EU, which, in the meantime, did not set this as a
term to the start of the accession talks.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman stressed that if other proposals are made
regarding Turkish Cypriot participation in the accession talks,
"they will be studied, but always measured against the
safeguarding of the legal government of the Republic as the sole
interlocutor in these negotiations."
</P>
<P>
He expressed satisfaction with the statements made Tuesday
by Jacques Poos, the president of the EU Council of Ministers
and Luxembourg Foreign Minister, on Cyprus' bid to become a member
of the EU.
</P>
<P>
Poos said after a meeting with Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis
Kasoulides that the EU would abide by all its decisions and
fulfill obligations it had assumed regarding the start of the
EU-Cyprus accession talks which was reaffirmed by the EU in July
to begin early next year.
</P>
<P>
the Turkish Cypriot side, however, rejected EU's decision to
start Cyprus' accession talks and refused to further negotiate
settlements of the protracted Cyprus problem with the Cypriot
government after two rounds of U.N.-sponsored direct talks in July
and August.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus applied for EU membership in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third in the wake of a failed
coup by the Greek Cypriot seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared a breakaway "Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus," which was recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
</TEXT>
