<HEADLINE> Kenya Producers Urged to Eye Overseas Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan manufacturers should
double efforts to expand overseas market so as to make Kenya
become a newly industrialized state in the next century, Vice
President George Saitoti said here today.
</P>
<P>
"I urge the Kenyan producers and manufacturers to look outward
to the regional and other markets," and to make their products
more competitive worldwide, he said at the opening ceremony of
the 23rd New Kenya Trades Exhibition.
</P>
<P>
However, he lamented that within the Common Market for Eastern
and Southern Africa (COMESA), the main destination of Kenya
manufactured goods exports, "there is a gradual decline and
consequential shortfall in meeting the targets set."
</P>
<P>
The down trend is partly due to tariff barriers against Kenyan
products adopted by some COMESA members contrary to the COMESA
Treaty signed by 10 southern and eastern African states in 1993
with a goal to set up a full free trade area by 2000, he said.
</P>
<P>
"In order to increase our exports in the region, the Kenyan
government will continue to provide an enabling environment for
our industries so that they are able to produce competitive
products," Saitoti pledged.
</P>
<P>
The annual exhibition, a leading indoor industrial and
commercial show in the COMESA region, is expected to help
participants capture and retain regional and other export
markets, according to the organizers.
</P>
<P>
The five-day fair, under the theme of "Trade Challenges in the
Regional Market", has attracted almost 70 exhibitors, five of
them from China, Italy, Tanzania, Indonesia and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of items of commodities and merchandise including
toys, textiles, home and office furnishing, processed food and
beverage, plastic ware, paper products, plaited craft, coffee,
building materials are on the display. 
</P>
</TEXT>
