<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Increases in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Underlying inflation went up
in August with the three-months annualized rate rising to 4.2
percent from negative 0.8 percent in July, according to the
latest monthly economic review by Central Bank of Kenya (CBK).
</P>
<P>
CBK said the underlying inflation jumped due to depreciation
of the Shilling against major convertible currencies early last
month following the key loan cut by the International Monetary
Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
CBK said reduced expansion in money supply and credit by the
banking system however helped moderate the effects on inflation
of the loss of the Shilling on the foreign exchange market.
</P>
<P>
The bank added that the overall month-on-month inflation fell
to 7.7 percent last month from 8.9 percent in July due to
improved supply of basic foods.
</P>
<P>
The decline in overall inflation was in goods and services
consumed by the lower income group whose month-on-month rate
dropped to 7.8 percent last month from 9.8 percent in July.
</P>
<P>
But the month-on-month inflation for the middle and upper
income groups increased respectively to 7.5 percent and 10.9
percent from 5.7 percent and 8.5 percent in July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
