<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Ex-Leader Hails Chinese Leadership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's former head of state
chief Earnest Shonekan today congratulated the Chinese leaders
for the rapid economic growth China has achieved in recent years.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, Shonekan said he would like to
congratulate the Chinese leaders for the vision they have "to see
things ahead and to put appropriate measures in place".
</P>
<P>
According to him, it is the foresight of the Chinese leaders
to liberalize the national economy to some extent, send
businesses to play in the global field, and promote technological
advancement that results in China's fast economic growth which is
"very very exemplary".
</P>
<P>
Shonekan, who visited China last October, is chairman of the
vision 2010 committee, which has been drawing Nigeria's first
national long-term socio-economic development blueprint since
November last year.
</P>
<P>
The way by which China scores the rapid development in such a
short time "needs to be copied by all countries", because no
country has ever made such achievements in a single stretch, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Shonekan, who called himself businessman instead of
politician, made these remarks prior to the 15th National
Congress of the Communist Party of China (CPC) scheduled to open
the coming Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the forthcoming CPC congress is expected to
make decisions on further implementing China's socio-economic
development program so as to steadily push the reforms forward in
the country.
</P>
<P>
As for the reform policies and measures China has been
carrying out these years, Shonekan said: "This is one of the
things I think you should continue."
</P>
<P>
Further reform will help China attract more foreign investment
and boost the transfer of Chinese funds and technology overseas,
especially to developing countries, and Africa in particular,
thus having an impact on the world economy.
</P>
<P>
It will also improve the competitiveness of Chinese
enterprises in the global market, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
