<HEADLINE> Iran Calls on EU to Reconsider Ban on Pistachio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Iran called today on the
European Union (EU) to reconsider its decision to suspend
importing pistachio from Iran.
</P>
<P>
In a statement published here today, the Iranian Ministry of
Agriculture called EU's decision "hasty" and said the Iranian
pistachio is "toxin-free."
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the government supervises the
mechanized process of pistachio's harvest and production through
tight quality control and laboratory methods to ensure that the
products meet international standards.
</P>
<P>
The EU said Tuesday that it had banned imports of pistachio
from Iran because of fears of contamination by Aflatoxin B1, a
carcinogenic substance produced by molds.
</P>
<P>
The EU imported from Iran 83,700 tonnes of pistachio worth 14
million U.S. dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
A report issued by Iran's Ministry of Agriculture in 1995 shows
that 59 percent of world's pistachio is produced in Iran. It
harvests about 210,000 tonnes of pistachio annually, half of which
is exported, earning 400 million dollars in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
