<HEADLINE> Angola's Opposition UNITA Strives to Avoid UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The opposition National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) is sparing no effort
to implement the Lusaka peace accord before the UN's decision of
imposing sanctions on it takes effect on September 30.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed here today by special envoy of the United
Nations to Angola Blondin Beye when addressing diplomatic
missions based in Angola on the development of its peace process.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that the UNITA has many difficulties in
meeting all the provisions of the peace agreement before the UN
Security Council's resolution on sanctions against UNITA comes
into force.
</P>
<P>
To avoid the UN's sanctions, first of all, the UNITA has to
allow the government of national unity to reestablish local
government organs in the areas under its control, such as
Bailundo, Andulo, Kuango and Mavinga, which are of great
strategic importance to UNITA.
</P>
<P>
This is a serious challenge to UNITA, said Beye.
</P>
<P>
The UNITA also has to completely disarm its troops, which is
worried by international community, according to the UN envoy.
</P>
<P>
As for the status of the UNITA controlled radio, Beye said
that much progress has been made, adding that the radio's hostile
propaganda have reduced drastically.
</P>
<P>
But it is not easy to solve all the three outstanding problems
within twenty days, the UN official stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
