<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Finances India's Coal Sector Rehabilitation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today
announced the approval of 531.5 million U.S. dollars in financing
for the coal sector rehabilitation project in India.
</P>
<P>
The main objectives of the project are to back the
market-oriented reforms in the country's coal sector and,
especially, to provide financial and technical support to Coal
India, which is the largest public sector enterprise in the
country and one of the world's largest coal companies in terms of
production, in its efforts to become commercially viable and
self-sustaining.
</P>
<P>
The project is also aimed to increase domestic supplies of coal
by financing investment in 24 of its most profitable open-cast
mines of Coal India until imports and production from private
investment can fill the emerging supply gap.
</P>
<P>
The financing consists of a 530 million dollar loan and a 1.5
million credit channeled through the International Development
Association, the World Bank's concessionary lending arm for
developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
