<HEADLINE> UN: No Cut in Palestinian Refugee Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Relief and
Works Agency (UNRWA) today announced that it had abandoned its
planned budget cut of 20 million U.S. dollars after several
consecutive days of Palestinian refugees' protests in Arab
countries.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by Lionel Brisson, director of UNRWA
in Lebanon, following a meeting with Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri here, according to Lebanese official National News Agency.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that the donor nations to UNRWA, the sole
provider of social welfare to the 3.3 million Palestinian refugees
in the world, held a meeting today in Jordan's capital of
Amman. They agreed to cover 19 million U.S. dollars out of the 20
million U.S. dollars deficit in the organization's overall budget,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Another 1 million U.S. dollars must also be raised, he added,
hoping the matter should be settled down in this year.
</P>
<P>
He said that the organization had given up all its
spending-saving measures it had announced before, especially in
health care and education services.
</P>
<P>
The new budget for next year will be discussed in the UN's
General Assembly, he added.
</P>
<P>
On August 25, Brisson delivered a letter to Lebanese Foreign
Minister Fares Boueiz informing him of the reduction of 20 million
U.S. dollars in this year's budget of 54.7 million U.S. dollars
due to the lack of contributions from donor countries.
</P>
<P>
The decision provoked several days of protests by Palestinian
refugees in Lebanon and other host countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
