<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FBI Tries to Minimize Damage to Saudi Bombing Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The FBI director tried on
Wednesday to minimize the damage to the probe into the 1996 truck
bombing in Saudi Arabia after the Justice Department decided to
drop the charge against a Saudi suspect who was believed to have
link to the attack.
</P>
<P>
Louis Freeh said the FBI would have preferred that Hani
al-Sayegh, the Saudi suspect brought from Canada by the United
States, had followed through on an earlier plea agreement to admit
his guilt to an unrelated terrorist charge and to help U.S.
investigators make a probe into the Khobar Towers truck bombing
under the condition that he would not be extradited to Saudi
Arabia, his home country.
</P>
<P>
But according to a statement issued on Monday by the Justice
Department, Sayegh had not provided the requisite evidence, and
prosecution against him had to be "withdrawn."
</P>
<P>
The failure to draw any evidence on the Khobar Towers bombing,
which killed 19 American servicemen, from Sayegh was a blow to the
FBI investigators, but Freeh told a briefing they would "work that
case with every resource and with the greatest intensity possible"
to minimize the damage, caused by Sayegh's "reneging on that
agreement."
</P>
<P>
"It is our intention to do whatever we need to do for as long
as it takes to bring a charge and prosecution against those
responsible" for the bombing, he said. Freeh said the FBI
continues to work closely with Saudi Arabia to acquire evidence
about the bombing. But the FBI has not been able to directly
question any suspect in Saudi Arabia, he said.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the FBI had evidence linking Sayegh to the bombing
attack, Freeh said: "We have received a lot of information from
our counterparts." But he said some of the evidence would be
inadmissible in U.S. court for a criminal prosecution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-10 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Opposition Leader Warns of War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Meeting with United States
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright late today, Israeli
opposition Labor party leader Ehud Barak warned that the current
crisis in the Israeli-Arab peace process could lead to war.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference held after his 50-minute meeting
with Albright, Barak said that the meeting focused on the issue of
fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Barak, the hawkish former Army Chief of Staff voiced his full
support to the Likud government in demanding Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) to launch a war against Islamic militant
organizations, such as the Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas) and
Islamic Jihad.
</P>
<P>
Hamas has claimed responsibility for the suicide bombing
attacks in Jerusalem on July 30 and September 4, that killed 25
people and wounded over 300 others and have aggravated the crisis
in the Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
But Barak pointed out that the major difference between his
party and the Likud government was that his party regarded
political negotiations as the only way to solve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said he favored a temporary halt to the construction of the
Har Homa settlement in East Jerusalem, which sparked the current
peace stalemate, in order to rebuild confidence between Israel
and the PNA.
</P>
<P>
Barak warned that the continued deterioration of the situation
in the peace process would lead to war. He said this was
unnecessary and thus should be prevented through making efforts to
resume the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
He added that he and Albright also discussed the tensions in
South Lebanon, where 13 Israeli soldiers were killed in clashes
with anti-Israeli Hezbollah guerrilla forces last Friday.
</P>
<P>
He said he was opposed to the unilateral Israeli pullout from
south Lebanon. He demanded international peacekeepers or Lebanese
forces be deployed to replace the Israeli troops stationed there
since 1985 to maintain its self-claimed south Lebanon security
zone.
</P>
<P>
Barak said he also requested Albright's help in securing the
release of Israeli citizen Azzam Azzam, who was sentenced to 15
years in prison on August 31 by an Egyptian court for spying for
Israel. He strongly denied that Azzam was a spy.
</P>
<P>
Albright, on her first Middle East tour since taking office, is
scheduled to visit Syria, Egypt, Jordan and Saudi Arabia after
holding rounds of talks with Israeli and Palestinian leaders here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
