<HEADLINE> UNRWA Revokes Cuts in Services for Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Relief and
Work Agency (UNRWA) decided today to revoke some planned
cuts in services for millions of Palestinian refugees in the
region after winning pledges of fresh fundings.
</P>
<P>
UNRWA Commissioner-General Peter Hansen said at a press
conference here that he was able to revoke the cuts after winning
over 22 million U.S. dollars in new pledges from the agency's 26
donor countries for its regular programs in 1997, Radio Jordan
reported.
</P>
<P>
His decision followed Tuesday's donors' meeting in Amman,
during which some of the donors pledged to contribute more funds
to offset the agency's 20 million dollars deficit for fiscal
year 1997.
</P>
<P>
Due to the deficit, the UNRWA, which is in charge of helping
some 3 million Palestinian refugees in Jordan, Syria, Lebanon,
the West Bank and Gaza Strip, planned austerity measures earlier
this year to cut down its regular services.
</P>
<P>
These measures included imposition of tuition fees on school
children, freezing the appointment of teachers and reduction in
hospitalization programs and medical treatment services.
</P>
<P>
The measures triggered off widespread criticism from the Arab
world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
