<HEADLINE> Zambian Ex-president Kaunda to Be Sued for Libel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Zambian ex-president Kenneth
Kaunda is to be sued for alleging that two officers in the Office
of President had tried to assassinate him.
</P>
<P>
The official Zambia News Agency ZANA today quoted Kafumba
Mboma, lawyer for the affected officers Max Kaona and Lameck
Malambo, as saying that his firm is going ahead to sue Kaunda for
libel since the ex-president refused to apologize to his clients
for linking them to an assassination plot.
</P>
<P>
Lawyers for the two officers set a deadline last Thursday for
Kaunda, president of the United National Independence Party
(UNIP), to offer an apology within 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
The 73-year old former president, who led Zambia to
Independence from Britain in 1964 and ruled the country until
1991, named the two officers as being among those who allegedly
wanted to assassinate him in a shooting accident late August, in
which he and another opposition leader were wounded.
</P>
<P>
The lawyers said that the allegations leveled against their
clients were grave and put them in danger and also demanded
compensation.
</P>
<P>
But a senior official of the UNIP said on Tuesday that the
party saw no reason for Kaunda to apologize because the
allegation was true.
</P>
<P>
Mboma told ZANA that therefore, he and his colleagues will go
ahead in pursuing the case to its "logical" conclusion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
