<HEADLINE> Cameroun to Halt Employment of Child Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Simon Mbila, Cameroun's
minister of labor and social insurance, today reiterated the
government's resolve to effectively dissuade the involvement of
child between the ages of 6 and 14 in the labor force.
</P>
<P>
Mbila made the remarks here this morning while presiding over
the opening ceremony of a two-day seminar on the fight against
child labor in the country.
</P>
<P>
The seminar which is organized by the Cameroun's Ministry of
Labor and Social Insurance in collaboration with the
International Labor Organization (ILO) is designed to contribute
ideas toward the finalization of a national action plan for the
fight against child labor.
</P>
<P>
The minister announced Cameroun's intention to join other
modern states to apply the UN Convention on the Right of
Children.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that children were prompted prematurely
into the labor force by the permeating effects of economic
crisis.
</P>
<P>
About 80 participants including administrators and members of
non-governmental organizations have attended the seminar, which
will end tomorrow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
