<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Members of the U.S.
Congressional Black Caucus Foundation Wednesday urged President
Bill Clinton to support easing sentencing guidelines for low-level
drug offenders and to restore allocation to repair dilapidated
schools.
</P>
<P>
They also pledged to try to roll back what they described as
racist attempts to erode affirmative action programs -- an effort
to provide increased employment and education opportunities for
ethnic minorities and women, to over come past discrimination.
</P>
<P>
They said their primary goals are to eradicate drugs from black
communities and to promote education as the lodestone for a
successful life.
</P>
<P>
Preparing an agenda for the 105th Congress, Representative
Maxine Waters, a Democrat of California, said that black leaders
face a difficult task in the Republican-controlled House and
Senate.
</P>
<P>
Waters, chairwoman of the Congressional Black Caucus, spoke at
a news conference to mark the opening of the Black Caucus
Foundation's annual legislative conference.
</P>
<P>
She said a continuing source of irritation is the disparity of
the mandatory sentences meted out to mainly black people found in
possession of small amounts of crack cocaine and the far lighter
sentences often given to mainly white people found to possess
similar amounts of powdered cocaine.
</P>
<P>
Waters called is "totally unfair."
</P>
<P>
"We are going to continue to impress on the president to do the
right thing," she said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Waters said money is desperately needed to
repair dilapidated schools and to provide them with up-to-date
science and computer facilities.
</P>
<P>
She said the "measly five billion dollars" earmarked for that
effort got lost in budget negotiations between Clinton and
congressional Republicans.
</P>
<P>
"We want that money back," she said.
</P>
<P>
"Collectively, we can get some wins if we stop thinking of
ourselves as victims," she said. 
</P>
