<P>
These former soldiers of the Wehrmacht were subjected to
inhumane treatment, dangerous labor and constant threat of death,
and 23,000 of them died during the detention, according to the
daily.
</P>
<P>
Entitled "One Million Germans in France," the film was shot by
Stephane Khemis and Jean-Michel Gaillard and produced by
Henry-Claude de la Casiniere for the "Documents of History" serial
program of France 3 television channel.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the war, the Allied forces had captured about 10
million German POWs, and 1 million of them were imprisoned in
France.
</P>
<P>
Some survivors of the POWs said in the documentary that
although the Geneva Convention provisions require clean shacks for
POWs, distriction of food at a correct ration and sparing POWs
from dangerous labor, their experience in the camps was far from
that.
</P>
<P>
Walter Miksh, a former warrant officer of Luftwaffe, said that
he received "minimum food" and was subjected to "brutal treatment"
by the guard. Willi Lidle, a former SS soldier, said that the
French guards urinated upon the POWs in the truck cabins which
transported them.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, 3,000 German POWs were killed when defusing land
mines in France, said Raymond Aubrac, a famous French resistance
fighter who was in charge of the operation of defusing land mines
in the whole country, in his book "Where the Memory Comes Late."
</P>
<P>
It was only after a campaign by the Catholic press of France
that the French government began to improve the treatment of the
German POWs in 1947, said le Monde. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
