<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese PM Launches New Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto today reshuffled his cabinet immediately after his
re-election as president of the ruling Liberal Democratic Party
(LDP).
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto appointed Kanezo Muraoka as cabinet secretary to
replace Seiroku Kajiyama; former Chief Cabinet Secretary Keizo
Obuchi as foreign minister to succeed Yukihiko Ikeda; and Mitsuo
Horiuchi as minister of international trade and industry to
replace Shiji Sato.
</P>
<P>
But he retained three key ministers: Finance Minister Hiroshi
Mitsuzuka, Defense Agency Chief Fumio Kyuma, and Health and
Welfare Minister Junichiro Koizumi.
</P>
<P>
In a controversial move, the key cabinet post for Hashimoto's
reform programs, chief of the Management and Coordination Agency,
went to Koko Sato, who was convicted of accepting bribes in the
1970s Lockheed payoff scandal.
</P>
<P>
At a nationally televised press conference where the new
cabinet was introduced, newly named Chief Cabinet Secretary
Muraoka defended Sato's appointment, and said the main task of the
new cabinet is to implement the reforms pledged by Hashimoto.
</P>
<P>
"The case is over legally and he has long years of experience
as a Diet(parliament) member," he said, citing Sato's experience
in having served as head of the LDP's task force on administrative
reforms.
</P>
<P>
In May 1986, The Tokyo High Court gave Sato a two-year prison
term with a three-year suspension for taking 2 million yen in
bribes from All Nippon Airways in 1972 while serving as vice
transport minister.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto also named Ihei Ochi, a former transport minister, as
minister of agriculture, forestry and fisheries; Nobutaka
Machimura as education minister; Kokichi Shimoinaba as justice
minister; Hiroshi Oki as Environment Agency Chief; and Muneo
Suzuki as Chief of the Hokkaido and Okinawa Development agencies.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Koichi Kato retained his post as LDP secretary
general along with LDP Policy Affairs Research Council Chairman
Taku Yamasaki and LDP Executive Council Chairman Yoshiro Mori.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came after Hashimoto's re-election as LDP
president was formally endorsed at a plenary session of LDP
members from both houses of the Diet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
