<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos Calls for Calm, Unity Among Filipinos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos today called on all sectors for calm and unity in the midst
of the current currency crisis and the raging debate over
constitutional change in the country.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving for Europe and the Middle East, Ramos said in a
statement that "the stormy weather" over the country will soon
blow over, and the nation will continue on its course to economic
development.
</P>
<P>
In mentioning "stormy weather", Ramos was referring to the
ongoing debate over the proposed amendments to the constitution,
the currency crisis and the volatile stock market, said a press
release from the Presidential Press Office.
</P>
<P>
In this impromptu statement, Ramos appealed to his critics to
strengthen "the ship" which 70 million Filipinos are on board,
instead of putting holes on it.
</P>
<P>
Ramos accused some "heavyweights" among his critics of "seeing
certain opportunities for themselves in the current problems
besetting the country."
</P>
<P>
Ramos again called on his critics -- the opposition and the
Roman Catholic Church -- to be patient to wait till early November
when his ruling Lakas-NUCD party will reveal stance on some
"political issues."
</P>
<P>
Ramos' statement came just ten days before the opposition and
the powerful Catholic Church stage a massive rally in central
Manila to protest the drive to rewrite the constitution.
</P>
<P>
Also today, Senator Miriam Defensor-Santiago, one of the
prominent opposition leaders in the country, agreed to unite with
her rivals in the opposition camp against changes to the
constitution.
</P>
<P>
Santiago said she will join the September 21 rally along with
the United Opposition led by Vice President Joseph Estrada,
Senator Edgardo Angara and Senate President Ernesto Maceda.
</P>
<P>
Opposition leaders and Manila Archbishop Jaime Cardinal Sin
have accused Ramos of supporting the charter change drive in order
to run for a second term.
</P>
<P>
Ramos must step down in June 1998 when his constitutionally
mandated one single six-year term expires.
</P>
<P>
Ramos, who is now in Russia, will return home one day before
the protest rally. He will also visit Kuwait, the Czech Republic
and Austria.
</P>
<P>
Because of mounting concerns over political stability in the
country, both the local currency market and the stock market
witnessed turmoil today.
</P>
<P>
The average exchange rate between the Philippine peso and the
U.S. dollar today dropped further to 32.375 pesos to one dollar
from 31.947 pesos Wednesday. In the stock market, the main index
plunged 67.48 points to close at 2,145.29.  
</P>
</TEXT>
