<HEADLINE> Fighting Continues near Afghanistan's Northern City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Heavy fighting was
continuing today between Afghan Islamic Taliban fighters and their
rival forces for the control of Mazar-e-Sharif, the second largest
city in northern Afghanistan, Afghan sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban forces, which are now reportedly a few kilometers
away of the stronghold of anti-Taliban strongman Uzbek warlord
Abdul Malik, have flown in fresh reinforcements in preparations
for a final assault on the city, about 300 km north of Kabul, said
the sources in Peshawar, a major city in northwestern Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic student militia have asked the rival forces
defending Mazar-e-Sharif to lay down their arms, otherwise a major
offensive will be launched against them, they said.
</P>
<P>
According to foreign aid workers in Mazar-e-Sharif, fierce
fighting was raging in the eastern parts of the city and situation
for the anti-Taliban forces was alarming as some defected
commanders were in control of all the western roads leading to the
city, they said.
</P>
<P>
Forces loyal to Malik and his allies, Shiite group
Hezb-e-Wadhat and Harakat-e-Islami, have launched a series of
counter-attacks on Taliban to secure their control of
Mazar-e-Sharif amid incidents of looting in the city, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Malik's another ally, Afghanistan's former military
chief Ahmad Masood launched a major attack on Taliban positions in
eastern Takhar Province, according to another report monitored
here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Masood, whose forces are within 20 km north of Taliban
controlled capital of Kabul, has been battling the hard-line
militia there for the past two months.
</P>
<P>
Malik, who took control of Mazar-e-Sharif late May after
turning against his former boss Rashid Dostum, briefly sided with
Taliban, allowing them into northern Afghanistan unopposed. But
only after five days, in a dispute over power-sharing, he drove
the Islamic militia out again.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, who now control about two-thirds of Afghanistan's
territory and the capital of Kabul, have vowed to impose a strict
Islamic rule in the war-torn country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
