<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Honest Australian Mother Showered With Rewards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- A single Australian mother,
who accepted a 50 Australian dollar (36 U.S. dollar) reward for
returning a 75,000 Australian dollar (54,750 U.S. dollar) prize
winning lottery ticket, was today showered with gifts from
well-wishing strangers for her honesty.
</P>
<P>
Alison Bridger, 25, who found the winning lotto scratch card in
a rubbish bin while working her part-time job as a Perth service
station attendant, was the topic of heated talk-back radio debate
today in Perth, a coastal city in Western Australia.
</P>
<P>
Staff at the Gull Service Station where Bridger works every
Friday were contacted throughout today by strangers offering
cheque donations, the Australian Associated Press (AAP) reported.
</P>
<P>
Bridger, a mother of a two and a half year-old child, said she
appreciated the gifts but did not understand the motivation.
</P>
<P>
"Sure I thought about keeping it but it wasn't mine," she said.
</P>
<P>
"I wouldn't have been able to live with myself if I kept it so
it was an easy decision to give it back."
</P>
<P>
She said she had been offered a 100 Australian dollar (73 U.S.
dollar) reward from the winner but had only accepted 50 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The unspecified winner, however, was not the only lucky person
in Perth.
</P>
<P>
 The honesty of staff at a Perth petrol station saved an
absent-minded father from missing out on a 54,750 U.S. dollar
fathers' day windfall, The West Australian Lotteries Commission
was quoted by AAP as saying on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A local newsagent confirmed on Monday the two Australian
dollar (1.4 U.S. dollar) scratchy the 82-year-old man's son had
given him for father's day was a winner.
</P>
<P>
But when he arrived at the Lotteries Commission to collect his
prize, the man realized the ticket, which he had been using as a
bookmark in a street directory, was missing.
</P>
<P>
A panic-stricken search ensued, including calls to the
newsagent and other places the man had stopped to ask directions.
</P>
<P>
Later that day, the man's daughter received a phone call from
a Gull Service Station in Perth, to say the ticket had been found.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
