<HEADLINE> Immigrants In Shanghai Set Up Their Own School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Immigrant workers in
Shanghai, China's largest trade center, have used 100,000 yuan
(12,000 US dollars) to set up a primary school for their
children.
</P>
<P>
The school, located in Minhang District, is the first
school for children of migrant workers. It now has seven
teachers and 150 pupils in five grades.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Education Department is managing the school while
a counterpart in Pucheng in Fujian province, the home of the
migrant workers, is responsible for the textbooks and arranging
courses.
</P>
<P>
There are over 10,000 people of Pucheng working in Shanghai.
It is diffficult for many of their children to be enroled in
Shanghai schools becuase they are not permanent residents of the
city. The school was established because parents were afraid they
might become illiterate.
</P>
<P>
Chen Changqi, president of the school and one of its sponsors,
owns a furniture shop in Shanghai which earns about ten million
yuan (1.2 million US dollars) annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
