<HEADLINE> Foreign Fund Managers Confident of Malaysia's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Foreign fund managers
have expressed their confidence that Malaysia's fundamentals are
still intact and that there is no cause for concern, Malaysian
government's economic adviser Tun Daim Zainuddin said today.
</P>
<P>
Daim, who met with several fund managers last week, said, "We
will continue to meet them and have so far cleared their doubts
about the country's current account deficit and the so-called mega
projects."
</P>
<P>
"They now understand and we will continue to listen to the
voice of the business community," he was quoted by the Malaysian
national news agency Bernama as saying after launching "Malaysia
Today", a publication by Malaysia's Asian Strategy and Leadership
Institute (ASLI).
</P>
<P>
Daim said Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad will be meeting with
several fund managers this weekend.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim is scheduled to
attend a dialogue with fund managers here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, who is also finance minister, announced several measures
aimed at easing inflationary pressures and reducing the current
account deficit last night at a dinner hosted by the Association
of Banks in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The measures included a two percent cut in government
expenditure, deferment of decisions on privatization of
government projects and a review of large purchases of foreign
goods by government agencies including the Armed Forces.
</P>
<P>
Misinformation has led to confusion about the state of the
economy, Daim said, adding that as Malaysia continues to reach
greater economic height and play a pivotal role in the
international scene, genuine interest and the search for accurate
information about Malaysia becomes more complex and varied.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the present currency crisis and the decline in
the stock market will not lead Malaysia into a recession, saying
that economic fundamentals remain strong.
</P>
<P>
The present situation is of a transient nature, he said. "What
is important is that we should not lose confidence of the present
system and take a long term view of the economy."  
</P>
</TEXT>
