<HEADLINE> Guinea Detains 3 S. Leone Security Officers: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, September 11 (xinhua) -- State radio in Sierra Leone
said today that three Sierra Leone security officers were
detained by the Guinean government authorities Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Sierra Leone military government information division was
quoted by the radio as saying that the three, Colonel Komba
Mondeh, Major Fangay Turay and a paramilitary Corporal were
allegedly "involved in clandestine activities that threatens the
security of the two sister republics of Guinea and Sierra Leone."
</P>
<P>
The radio did not specify the nature of the investigations but
said the military government is "assuring the public that all
subversive activities aimed at derailing peace and stability in
Sierra Leone will be nipped in the bud."
</P>
<P>
The radio also announced that a truckload of arms and
ammunition allegedly purchased by two former ministers in the
ousted civilian government of Tejan Kabbah, has been intercepted
by Ghanaian troops in the west African peace-keeping force
(Ecomog) in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
The two have been identified as former Mineral Resources
Minister Dr Prince Harding and former deputy Defense Minister
Hinga Norman.
</P>
<P>
"The arms were intercepted on Wednesday by Ghanaian troops
acting on a tip-off, seizing the truck which was on its way to
the border town of Zimmi (in the east of Sierra Leone)," the
radio said.
</P>
<P>
The radio accused Nigerian troops in Ecomog of "training and
equipping Kamajor militiamen" to destabilize Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
It said the ammunition were purchased through the
collaboration of the Ecomog Field Commander, General Victor Malu.
But the Ecomog Ground Commander in Sierra Leone, Colonel Max
Khobe has denied the allegation. 
</P>
