<HEADLINE> UN Concerned About Renewed Fighting in Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations today
expressed deep concern over recent renewed fighting in northern
Afghanistan and appealed to Afghan warring parties for an
immediate ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations is "deeply disturbed" by the renewed
fighting in northern Afghanistan, which is posing an additional
threat to the very territorial unity of the country itself, said
Norbert Holl, head of the U.N. Special Mission to Afghanistan, in
a press release issued here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The continuing armed struggle in Afghanistan is also splitting
the Afghan people along ethnic, religious and regional lines, he
said. "This makes the goal of national reconciliation and peace
yet more elusive and difficult to achieve."
</P>
<P>
Holl also reiterated that the route to stability and peace in
Afghanistan is through ceasefire and negotiations among the
warring factions in the spirit of tolerance and mutual
accommodation.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. special envoy renewed his strong appeal to the Afghan
warring parties to stop fighting immediately and to accept the
long-standing invitation of the U.N. for serious intra-Afghan
dialogue to resolve the national crisis.
</P>
<P>
"It is never too late to begin these negotiations through the
good offices of the United Nations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Over the past three days, fierce fighting has been raging
between the Afghan Islamic Taliban fighters and their rival forces
around the strategic town of Mazar-e-Sharif, about 300 kilometers
north of Kabul. 
</P>
</TEXT>
