<HEADLINE> America's Cup Destroyer Jailed for 34 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- A New Zealand court on
Thursday jailed for 34 months a Maori rights protester who
flattened the America's Cup, the world's oldest sporting trophy,
with a sledge-hammer.
</P>
<P>
According to a report here, Benjamin Peri Nathan, 28, attacked
the trophy at the Royal New Zealand Yacht Squadron headquarters in
Auckland on March 14. New Zealand won the trophy in 1995 in one of
the country's greatest sporting moments.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, a jury found him guilty of wilful damage
and in the Auckland District Court Judge Barry Morris sentenced
Nathan to two years and 10 months in prison.
</P>
<P>
The sentence will be served in addition to an 18-month prison
term Nathan is already serving for aggravated robbery and
demanding with menace.
</P>
<P>
Nathan had no regrets about the attack except to apologise for
frightening those in the room who watched him belt the case and
the cup up to 50 times with a short-handled sledgehammer.
</P>
<P>
The judge said he took into account that Nathan had a 12-year
history of appearing before the courts, which included 16 past
convictions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
