<HEADLINE> British Judiciary Chief Ends Visit to HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Lord Chancellor
Lord Irvine of Lairg ended today a five-day Hong Kong tour which
aimed to "further judicial and legal relations between Hong Kong
and Britain."
</P>
<P>
The judicial chief from London is the first high-ranking
British government official visiting Hong Kong since the handover.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Lord Irvine met with Andrew Li, the chief justice of
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR).
</P>
<P>
After their meeting, Lord Irvine announced that, at the request
of Li, two serving British Law Lords will sit on the Court of
Final Appeal of the HKSAR to form part of the court's
non-permanent panel of judges.
</P>
<P>
Law Lords are members of the House of Lords, Britain's upper
house of parliament and highest court.
</P>
<P>
Britain has huge interests in Hong Kong, Lord Irvine told
reporters, adding he looked forward to the success of the HKSAR
under the "one country, two systems" principle.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Hong Kong, Lord Irvine also met with Acting
Chief Executive Anson Chan and Secretary for Justice Elsie Leung.
 
</P>
