<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Slightly Down on Jobs Data </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BZW Australia broker Jenny Gough said despite the release of
the August employment figures, which reflected a flat economy,
there had been little movement in the local bourse.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index finished down 0.7 point at 2665.8, off
a low of 2644.0.
</P>
<P>
In the interest rate sensitive bank sector, National Australia
Bank, Commonwealth Bank and Westpac, after all being down in
morning trade, closed on a higher note after the release of the
employment figures.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank rose 23 cents to 19.84 Australian
dollars, Commonwealth climbed 7.9 cents to 15.90 dollars, Westpac
edged up 2 cents to 8.10 dollars and ANZ Bank gained 6 cents to
close at 10.25 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index closed down 5.8 points to 1368.2, while
the all industrials index finished up 4.9 points at 4324.1.
</P>
<P>
In the resources and mining sectors, market bellwether BHP was
down 9 cents to 16.81 Australian dollars, WMC dropped 11 cents to
6.85 dollars, while Rio Tinto was up 16.5 cents at 20.18 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index closed down 12.8 points at 1291.4, with spot
trading in gold bullion at 320.95 U.S. dollars an ounce, down 45
U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 423.60 million shares traded worth
791.86 million Australian dollars (578.05 million U.S. dollars),
with falls of 621 outnumbering rises of 448.  
</P>
</TEXT>
