<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetans Making Money in Xodoin Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Early in the morning, Mima
Zholma and Basang Zholma carry their goods to Norbu Lingka, a park
in Lhasa, capital of Tibet, to do a little business during the
Xodoin Festival.
</P>
<P>
Xodoin was a traditional Tibetan drama festival that was
celebrated by displays of Buddhas and staging Tibetan dramas. In
the past it was mainly religious, and Norbu Lingka was the
entertainment capital of Tibetan aristocrats.
</P>
<P>
Now, however, the festival has begun to change into a trade
fair and Norbu Lingka has become a marketplace.
</P>
<P>
"In the past I came here merely for entertainment. But when I
see thousands of people crowding into Norbu Lingka, I know that
it's a good opportunity to make money," Mima Zholma says.
</P>
<P>
The sisters Zholma sold out their beer, mineral water, and
cigarettes, getting about 300 yuan (36 US dollars), in no more
than five hours.
</P>
<P>
Along the two-mile Norbu Lingka wall, tourists encounter
more than 1,000 booths and salesmen busily hawking their
goods. One old man is crying out to a visitor, "Come on buy a
bottle, it's home-made!" meaning his special highland barley
spirits.
</P>
<P>
The same scene is repeated in front of the Potala, and at the
foot of Zhebung Temple there are stands selling buttered tea to
pilgrims and tourists.
</P>
<P>
"Even the harsh natural conditions can't keep the booming
business down," one tourist said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East Asia Can Overcome Financial Turbulence: WB Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 11 (Xinhua) -- East Asia is well
positioned to overcome the current financial turbulence as long as
it enhances regulatory framework of financial system while
deepening structural reforms, according to a World Bank study
released here today.
</P>
<P>
The study, entitled "Are Financial Sector Weaknesses
Undermining the East Asian Miracle?", stresses that the region's
economies boast strong fundamentals, experienced macroeconomic
management, high savings and investment, and close integration
with the global economy.
</P>
<P>
Javad Shirazi, regional manager for strategy and partnerships
of the World Bank, is of the view that the region would continue
its dynamic growth despite the recent currency turmoil.
</P>
<P>
He told a press briefing here today: "There is every reason to
believe that, if macroeconomic and financial management is prudent
and countries adopt the structural measures needed to enhance the
competitiveness of their economies, East Asia will be able to ride
out the inevitable bumps on the road to a promising new century."
</P>
<P>
The study finds that even though East Asia has been the region
of "miracles" with world's fastest GDP growth for a decade, it is
not immune to short-term setbacks.
</P>
<P>
Stijn Claessens, World Bank principal economist in East Asia
and the Pacific and co-author of the study, pointed out that
although economies in the region have the fundamentals right, some
weak points do exist, notably large current account deficit,
excessive lending to property development and consumer credit,
non-performing loans and bad assets on banks' books, and weak
supervisory framework.
</P>
<P>
Currently, banking has dominated East Asia's financial sector,
but other parts of the financial systems, such as fixed income
market, equity market and pension funds, need further
development, he said.
</P>
<P>
He continued: "The penalties for maintaining a fragile,
under-developed financial system are severe, and the time to
correct structural weakness is much more compressed."
</P>
<P>
The study notes that robust and efficient financial systems
will only be achieved if countries adopt a consistent set of
reinforcing actions.
</P>
<P>
It recommends that East Asian countries need to redouble
efforts to strengthen institutional and incentive framework for
the financial system, including sound supervision and effective
mechanism to address bank failures.
</P>
<P>
The study also suggests gradual liberalization of financial
systems in East Asian countries. Internationalization of financial
services is of regional importance as foreign financial firms can
bring both competition and international standards and practice.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
