<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Favors ASEM Membership for Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The European Union said
today that it is in favor of giving Australia membership of the
Asia-Europe Summit (ASEM).
</P>
<P>
Sir Leon Brittan, vice-president of the European Commission --
the executive agency of the 15-nation union, said that he had "no
doubt whatsoever" that Australia is more than capable to make an
important contribution as a member of ASEM.
</P>
<P>
The senior EU official made this remark at a joint press
conference with visiting Australian deputy Prime Minister Tim
Fischer after EU and Australia held their 14th round of
ministerial consultations in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
Brittan said that the question of membership will certainly be
raised at the next ASEM summit to be held in London later this
year.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Bangkok ASEM summit in March 1996 was the
manifestation of the EU commitment to reinforce its relations with
Asia.
</P>
<P>
ASEM has started a close dialogue between Europe and Asia
across nearly all spheres ranging from politics, economy, culture,
education to science, he said.
</P>
<P>
A joint communique described the annual consultation, the first
since the signing in June of the joint declaration on relations
between EU and Australia, as being held in a friendly and open
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
Brittan and Fischer, who also serves as trade minister,
exchanged views on international as well as bilateral relations at
the consultation which touched upon such issues as latest
developments in the World Trade Organization, developments in the
Asia-Pacific region, prospects for the meeting of the framework
convention on climate change to be held this December in Kyodo,
Japan, and scientific and technological cooperation between EU and
Australia.
</P>
<P>
The EU and Australia are close economic partners. The EU is
Australia's largest merchandise trading partner and the largest
source of foreign investment in that country.
</P>
<P>
Many European companies have come to see Australia as a vital
bridgehead into markets in the Asia-Pacific region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
