<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto was officially re-elected as president of the ruling
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) today.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto's re-election was endorsed at a plenary session of LDP
members in both houses of the Diet (parliament).
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto will enter his second two-year term as LDP president
on October 1, while the ruling party's three top posts remain
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Koichi Kato retained his post as LDP secretary-general along
with LDP Policy Affairs Research Council Chairman Taku Yamasaki
and LDP Executive Council Chairman Yoshiro Mori, a LDP official
said.
</P>
<P>
An announcement on the new cabinet lineup is expected later
today, to be followed by a press conference by new ministers and
an inauguration ceremony at the Imperial Palace.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto was first elected LDP president in September 1995
with an overwhelming victory over his sole rival, Junichiro
Koizumi, the current Health and Welfare minister.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto took the helm of a coalition government of the LDP,
Social Democratic Party (SDP) and Sakigake in January 1996 from
Tomiichi Murayama, head of the SDP. 
</P>
