<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scots Vote in Devolution Referendum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- People in Scotland began
voting today in a historic referendum that will determine whether
the country can create its own parliament with the power to change
income tax level for the first time in three centuries.
</P>
<P>
Almost four million people are eligible to vote in 32
constituencies, and a majority of those voting will decide whether
the parliament should be created or not.
</P>
<P>
The voting began at 0600 GMT and ends at 2100 GMT. The first
results are expected shortly after midnight.
</P>
<P>
By 0300 GMT on Friday morning, the result should be decided
since more than 90 percent of the ballots will have been counted.
The final declaration, however, is unlikely until 1530 GMT on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
A yes vote will be followed by an election of a 129-strong
parliament, probably in May 1999 and would sit for the first time
in Edinburgh in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Wales will vote on a more limited degree of home rule a week
from today.
</P>
<P>
Opinion polls conducted earlier all showed an overwhelming
majority of voters in Scotland in favor of forming the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The governing Labor Party, the Liberal Democrats and the
pro-independence Scottish National Party have been campaigning for
a new Scottish Parliament with tax-raising powers, while the
opposition Conservative Party has been urging Scots to vote "NO."
</P>
<P>
Scotland was united with England in 1707, but so far it still
retains many of the characteristics of a national state, with its
own legal and education systems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
