<HEADLINE> Japanese PM Reshuffles Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO September 11 (Xinhua) _ Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto today reshuffled his cabinet immediately following his
re-election as president of the ruling Liberal Democratic Party
(LDP).
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto unveiled his new 21-member cabinet by introducing
them on national television.
</P>
<P>
The most notable change comes in the position of foreign
minister. Keizo Obuchi, the leader of the LDP's largest faction,
replaced Yukihiko Ikeda in the post.
</P>
<P>
But the LDP's three powerful executive posts: finance minister,
education and culture minister, and director-general of the
defense agency, remain unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Secretary General Koichi Kato, leader of the party's moderate
wing, and Taku Yamasaki, who chairs the party's Policy Affairs
Research Council, and Executive Council Chairman Yoshiro Mori also
retained their posts in the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto won a second two-year term as leader of the Liberal
Democratic Party during a plenary session of its lawmakers today.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time in the LDP's 42-year history that the
party president has been elected unopposed.
</P>
<P>
He can now stay on as prime minister until the next general
election, which need not be held for another two years. 
</P>
