<HEADLINE> Kohl Sees Potential for 3 Percent GDP Growth for 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FRANKFURT, September 11 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut
Kohl said today he expected Germany's gross domestic product (GDP)
to grow faster than the 2.5 percent the government forecast for
the year 1997.
</P>
<P>
"I'm pretty sure the growth will be near 3 percent," Kohl said
in a speech at the opening ceremony of the Frankfurt international
car show.
</P>
<P>
Although the current GDP growth is driven mainly by exports,
there is a reason for Germans to be optimistic and not just to
complain about weak domestic growth, Kohl said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed confidence that the export boom would stimulate
growth in domestic business in many sectors.
</P>
<P>
Kohl's remarks were apparently encouraged by official figures
released by the German Federal Statistics Office Wednesday, which
showed the German economy had grown 2.9 percent in the second
quarter and 2.0 percent in the first half of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
