<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High Criminal Rate in Somali Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Despite the lull of
factional fighting in the Somali capital, people here feel
insecure, as many are being killed, wounded and abducted by
gunmen in the past 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
A man was killed in north Mogadishu on late Wednesday
afternoon, as bullets hit him in the chest and six others were
wounded when unidentified gunmen opened fire at a car passing
through the crowded business area of Sana.
</P>
<P>
The wounded included three women of which one was a tea-shop
waiter. All of them were rushed to the ICRC-run hospital of
Keysaney.
</P>
<P>
Also Wednesday, only about 300 meters away from the same area,
a Toyota heading for the animal market was attacked by a group of
gunmen who looted the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
According to eyewitness, the gunmen had abducted the vehicle
with two elderly men on the front seat. No casualties were
reported in this incident. However, the fate of the two men
remained unknown as the gunmen drove the Toyota away to the
north.
</P>
<P>
Also in north Mogadishu, a group of heavily armed men attacked
the Yaqshid intermediate school. The neighbors of the school told
reporters that the gunmen attacked the premises with the
intention of robbing its furniture.
</P>
<P>
Volunteers from the neighborhood had fired at the raiders,
foiling their attempt of looting.
</P>
<P>
In south Mogadishu, too, a number of gunmen raided the house
of the director of Green Hope, a local non-governmental
organization. The owner of the house, Mr Jilal Barrow, was
seriously wounded in the head in the course of shooting.
</P>
<P>
As the gunmen couldn't find the target man, they grabbed the
son of Mr Barrow, a seven year old boy who still remains missing.
</P>
<P>
According to the neighbors, the gunmen are likely to ask for
ransom in an exchange of the safe release of the boy. this is not
the first time the Green Hope residence was attacked.
</P>
<P>
The increasing insecurity in the divided capital has also
attracted the attention of the faction leaders. The paralyzed
Islamic courts of north Mogadishu just two days ago sentenced 12
young men for three months imprisonment each for their so-called
misbehavior. The court has warned the militiamen against their
evil conducts.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, south Mogadishu faction leader, Hussein Mohamed
Aidid has summoned his newly formed committee in a bid to disarm
militiamen in south Mogadishu. But so far, no concrete action has
either been taken by Ali Mahdi or Hussein Aidid over the security
situation in the capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
