<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Leading TV Manufacturer Benefits from Reforms (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Changhong Electronics
Group, once a debt-ridden TV manufacturer, has become China's
biggest color TV producer and increased its capial 190-fold and
raised annual production capacity to 4.8 million TV sets in nine
years.
</P>
<P>
Ni Runfeng, general manager of the Sichuan company, explains
the economic miracle by pointing to the shareholding system in the
state sector.
</P>
<P>
The rags to riches story runs from 1987, when the group was a
small state-owned factory with fixed assets of 46 million
yuan. However, a decade later, Changhong now possesses 733 million
yuan in fixed assets, putting it first in China's electronics
industry.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the group's color TV output was 15 times the 1987
figure and pre-tax profits were 99 times that year's.
</P>
<P>
Ni is now regarded as one of the most prominent entrepreneurs
in Asia.
</P>
<P>
He told Xinhua that, like most of China's state-owned large and
medium-sized enterprises, Changhong was on the verge of
bankruptcy, resulting from a personnel surplus, inflexible
management, and a shortage of capital, technology, and brains nine
years ago.
</P>
<P>
But, "the shareholding reform saved Changhong from the
dangerous stagnation of the mid-1980s," he recalled. In 1988, the
group issued its first stock, raising 36 million yuan for a
self-designed production line, which helped the company bring its
color TV sets up to the international levels, and raising yearly
production capacity to one million sets.
</P>
<P>
Four years later, Changhong got another 100 million yuan from
stock sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Leading TV Manufacturer Benefits From Reforms (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Changhong has maintained its growth since it was listed on the
Shanghai Stock Exchange in March of 1994, with profits greater
than other listed companies for three years running.
</P>
<P>
According to Ni, Changhong has gotten three billion yuan from
stock over the past nine years.
</P>
<P>
Since 1991, it has set up 11 self-designed TV production lines,
expanding annual production capacity by more than four million TV
sets, and it now ranks among the top TV manufacturers in the world.
</P>
<P>
China's traditional state ownership blurred the difference
between the functions of the government and enterprises, resulting
in low efficiency, Ni said.
</P>
<P>
He added that a modern enterprise system with independent
management is badly needed to resuscitate the outmoded state-owned
firms and the shareholding system will be an efficient means of
doing so.
</P>
<P>
Ni said that the shareholding system allows enterprises to make
decisions based on a particular market situation, and will increase
their flexibility.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, there was cutthroat competition in China's color TV
market among Panasonic, Sony, Toshiba, Changhong, TCL, and
Congka. Changhong, leading domestic brands in the country-wide
price war, grew into the country's biggest television seller by
grabbing 27 percent of the country's TV market.
</P>
<P>
"The price war has reshaped the country's television market.
It would be impossible for an enterprise to use such violent
action under the planned economy," Ni said. "As an independent
stock-holding company, we fully enjoy planning and management
rights."
</P>
<P>
In 1994, Changhong's management publicized their plan to
establish a ten-million-yuan fund for poor university students --
without consulting the board of directors. The move was rejected
by stockholders until it was revised and approved by a meeting of
stockholders. "The event gave us an unforgettable lesson," Ni
said. "Any manager in a stock holding company should abide by the
bounds of the supervisory system."
</P>
<P>
Last year, the group purchased two TV factories in Jilin
and Jiangsu provinces to use as export bases, and is
expected to net five million US dollars in profits next year.
</P>
<P>
It is trying to develop into a multinational firm and has come up
with an ambitious plan to enter "the exclusive international club
of top 500 enterprises" by the beginning of the next century, with
annual output reaching eight million TV sets and sales of 30
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Parties Agree to Change Electoral System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government and
the parties in the country have agreed that the present electoral
system introduced in 1978 should be changed, a high-ranking
government official said today.
</P>
<P>
Justice and Constitutional Affairs Minister G.L. Peiris told a
press conference that the government had proposed a combination of
first-past-the-post system and proportional representation system.
</P>
<P>
This system is to strengthen the relationship between members
of the parliament and their constituents by having individual
electorates in place of the current district level system, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Under the current system, constituents don't know whom to go to
as the MPs represent a district and not an electorate.
</P>
<P>
But the minister added that a specific system is yet to be
arrived at.
</P>
<P>
The number of parliament seats would remain unchanged, Peiris
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
