<HEADLINE> Nigeria Vows to Continue Economic Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Head of State
General Sani Abacha has restated the government's commitment to
economic reform, saying the trend is "irreversible".
</P>
<P>
The numerous measures of the government to stabilize the
economy, reduce inflation, encourage savings, stimulate
investment and boost productivity have resulted in a remarkable
3.2 percent growth in the economy, Abacha disclosed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Similar progress has been achieved with the twin problems of
deficit financing and excess money spending in the economy," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Abacha also affirmed that the military administration's
"socio-political transformation program" which will lead to a
democratically-elected government next year was on course.
</P>
<P>
He made these remarks in the capital Abuja at the 27th yearly
Accountants' Conference of the Institute of Chartered Accountants
of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
His public appearance, which followed a report Monday that he
was seriously ill, is observed as something to douse speculations
of his health.
</P>
<P>
Abacha's words were echoed in the keynote speech at the
meeting delivered by Finance Minister chief Anthony Ani.
</P>
<P>
According to Ani, the government has put in place a number of
policy measures to integrate the Nigerian economy into the global
economy.
</P>
<P>
The measures aimed at opening up the national economy include
policies to enhance increased production, substantial output
growth and employment, as well as to encourage export and ensure
stable and efficient socio-economic environment.
</P>
<P>
They also cover policies to promotement privatization,
commercialization and liberalization of key growth-inducing
ventures.
</P>
<P>
He listed some of the achievements recorded so far, which
include the growth of direct foreign investment from 1,015.7
million U.S. Dollars in 1994 to 1,153.8 million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The government's fiscal surplus rose from 1.02 billion Naira
(about 12 million Dollars) in 1995 to 37 billion Naira (about 435
million) last year.
</P>
<P>
With a stable exchange rate, the country's gross domestic
product (gdp) went up from 1.3 percent in 1994 to 2.2 and 3.2
percent in the following two years respectively.
</P>
<P>
But he did not forget to warn: "although the 1997 budget
projected a real growth of gdp of 5.5 percent, it may be slightly
lower at the end of the period."
</P>
<P>
Despite these achievements, the tight money policy of the
government has also weakened purchase power of Nigerian
consumers, leading to increase of inventories of manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian manufacturers have been calling on the government to
take measures to boost domestic consumption so as to revitalize
the sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
