<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Investment Increases Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Domestic and foreign
investments in Indonesia have increased sharply during the last
five years, a government official said today.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's total domestic investments in 1993 were 39.4
trillion rupiah (17.13 billion U.S. dollars then) in 548 projects,
Investment Coordinating Board Secretary Mohamad Syukur said in
Palu, central Sulawesi.
</P>
<P>
Three years later in 1996, the number of projects jumped to
810, with total investments at 100.7 trillion rupiah (33 billion
U.S. dollars), according to the official.
</P>
<P>
During the first six months of this year, 446 projects worth
77.8 trillion rupiah (32.42 billion dollars) were approved, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, foreign investments had increased from 8.1 billion
dollars in 1993 to 29.9 billion dollars in 1996, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, foreign investments topped 16.4
billion dollars and the official said the upward trend will
continue.
</P>
<P>
Increasing investment, Syukur added, is a result of Indonesia's
strong economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
