<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 11 (Xinhua) -- General Motors'
Electro-Motive Division, one of the world's leading diesel
locomotive manufacturers, announced here today that it will open
an office in Beijing by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Most of the staff will be local people, according to Robert
L. Bolero, the company's Asia-Pacific Region manager.
</P>
<P>
Bolero spoke with reporters about the company's plan to look
for co-operation in China and said the company regards China as an
organic part of its global business, and hopes that it can equip
its locomotives with parts made by joint ventures in China.
</P>
<P>
The company wants to use its expertise and advanced technology
in diesel electric freight and passenger locomotives, he said.
</P>
<P>
The US giant was founded in 1922 and now has over 65 percent of
the international market, and has sold over 56,000 locomotives to
65 countries.
</P>
<P>
Professor Yang Chao, from the North China Communications
University, said that China imported 427 GM locomotives in
the '80s.
</P>
<P>
He said that China still has many things to learn from advanced
countries, especially in manufacturing heavy-load, high-speed
locomotives. 
</P>
