<HEADLINE> HK Tourism Sees Record Earnings in Fiscal 96/97 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's tourism
industry achieved record earnings of 104.8 billion HK dollars
(13.44 billion U.S. dollars) in foreign exchange in the fiscal
year 1996-1997, it was announced today.
</P>
<P>
Lo Yuk Sui, chairman of the Hong Kong Tourist Association
(HKTA), said at the association's 39th annual meeting today that
visitor arrivals in the fiscal year were also a record 11.7
million.
</P>
<P>
"Tourism is now the leading foreign exchange earner among Hong
Kong's service industries," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong enjoys a 9.2 percent share of major tourist markets,
ranking the eighth in the world, he said, adding that tourism also
provides about 360,000 jobs for the people of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
He said that Hong Kong's tourism and transportation
infrastructure is currently being transformed. By the end of year 2000,
close to 16,000 new hotel rooms are expected to be in service;
while the new airport at Chek Lap Kok will initially increase
passenger handling capacity to 35 million a year, with
an ultimate capacity of 87 million.
</P>
<P>
Amy Chan, executive director of the HKTA, said that the Hong
Kong Exposition being planned is financially viable as well as
logistically and technically feasible, as the findings from a
feasibility study demonstrate.
</P>
<P>
The Exposition will showcase Hong Kong as the leading business
and service center in Asia, position Hong Kong as the gateway to
the mainland, and position the inland areas as the major business
partner in Asia, she added. 
