<HEADLINE> Jordan Cautiously Optimistic over Albright's Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Information Minister
Samir Mutawe today expressed optimism, with an "if," over the
current regional tour of U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright who is now in Israel.
</P>
<P>
"If she forwards new ideas that could boost security
coordination and implementation of signed agreements between the
Palestinians and Israel," she would succeed in her mission to
salvage the deadlocked peace march, Mutawe said in a telephone
interview with the Cairo-based Voice of Arabs radio.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that focusing solely on the security issue as
Israel wants will never help achieve a just and comprehensive
peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated the importance of Israel's withdrawal from all
occupied Arab territories in order to bring about a just and
comprehensive peace for all parties.
</P>
<P>
Albright has been strongly criticized by Palestinian officials
for her statement following her talks Wednesday with Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu. They called on her to adopt a
balanced stance that could help achieve peace and security for all.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the Middle East News Agency today,
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat's
advisor Marwan Kanfani expressed deep concern over Albright's
adoption of the Israeli stance in general, especially with regard
to the settlement issue.
</P>
<P>
"Albright should have waited until after her meeting with
Arafat before making her statement," he said.
</P>
<P>
Albright will visit Egypt and Jordan starting Friday, the only
Arab countries to have peace treaties with Israel, after ending
trips to Israel, Palestinian self-rule areas and Syria.
</P>
<P>
Her tour to the region was aimed at reviving the
Palestinian-Israeli negotiations that stalled since March due to
Israeli construction of a controversial Jewish settlement in
Arab East Jerusalem. 
</P>
