<HEADLINE> Three S. Leone Army Officers Defect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, September 11 (xinhua) -- Three senior military
officers of the Sierra Leone army have defected after completing
a year's senior staff course in Nigeria, defense sources told
Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
Former Chief of Defense Staff, Colonel Komba Mondeh and former
camp Commander, Colonel Sam Mboma had been at the Nigeria Armed
Forces Command and Staff College in Jaji in Kaduna since July
last year while the third officer, former staff officer, Major
John Sowa joined them in January for a four-month junior staff
course, one source said.
</P>
<P>
The three officers who should have reported for duty in
Freetown Wednesday have now been dismissed, said the source.
</P>
<P>
Mondeh, who was a key player in the 1992 military coup which
overthrew the civilian government of Joseph Momoh, was a
Secretary of State for Marine Resources in the military
government set up by Captain Valentine Strasser. He later became
Chief of Defense Staff before the military government was
replaced by general elections in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Observers said Mondeh is now with ousted president Tejan
Kabbah in Guinea, a statement confirmed the fact by the
clandestine radio which this morning carried an interview with
Mondeh.
</P>
<P>
Mondeh in the interview warned junta leader Major Johnny Paul
Koroma ''to hand over power to Kabbah without delay or face the
consequences.''
</P>
<P>
''Koroma is too relatively junior to implement any meaningful
changes in the lives of the Sierra Leoneans,'' Mondeh said.
</P>
<P>
The other two officers have not been traced. Two senior
military officers, Lt. Colonel Tamba Momdu and Lt. Colonel Tam
Lettie who completed a year's senior staff course in the Armed
Forces College at Teshi in Ghana, returned home Wednesday, the
military said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
