<HEADLINE> HK Hotel Occupancy Plummets in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Figures from the Hong Kong
Tourist Association (HKTA) showed that hotel occupancy plummeted
to 58 percent in July from its year-ago level of 87 percent, the
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
And the decline seemed to forecast a worse hotel occupancy this
 year than last year, said HKTA Chairman Lo Yuk-sui.
</P>
<P>
He blamed the disappointing hotel take-up on the monetary
turmoil in Southeast Asia which resulted in a decline in tourist
arrivals from countries of the region.
</P>
<P>
The total number of Southeast Asian tourists coming to Hong
Kong dropped by a dramatic 30 percent in July compared with a year
 ago.
</P>
<P>
"The next three months will be the crucial period. We have
taken remedial measures but these may not have an immediate
effect," Lo said.
</P>
<P>
He expected that the World Bank-International Monetary Fund
conference to be held later this month might help boost hotel
occupancy for September.  
</P>
</TEXT>
