<HEADLINE> Angolan Peace Process at Crucial Point </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Portuguese State Secretary
for Foreign Affairs and Cooperation Jose Lamego said today the
Angolan Peace Process is now at a crucial point, urging the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) to
"take a remarkable step."
</P>
<P>
Lamego made the statement here when he arrived in the airport
to start his three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
He said that Portugal and the other two observers of the Angolan
Peace Process, the United States and Russia, all believed that all
parties involved, especially UNITA, should solve the current
difficulties though political means instead of confrontations.
</P>
<P>
Referring to UN resolution to impose sanctions on UNITA, the
secretary said, once the resolution goes into force, Portugal,
like the entire international community, will carry it out since
the resolution reflects the attitude of the world.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether Portuguese armed forces in the UN observers'
mission have any plan for withdrawal, Lamego said, the UN mission
will not expire until next February, and Portugal will have no
plan for withdrawal in addition to this date.
</P>
<P>
During his three-day visit, Lamego is expected to hold talks
with Angolan President, Foreign Minister and UN special envoy in
Angola on issues concerning the peace process. 
