<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Pessimistic About Situation in Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine today expressed pessimism over the solution of the
Algerian conflict in the near future, and compared the present
situation in Algeria to that of 1962, when the French colonial
rule collapsed.
</P>
<P>
In a speech at a conference of the Socialist Party held in
Montpellier, southern France, Vedrine said that the "fresh
break-out of violence" in Algeria seemed to be the response by
Islamic militants to the proposals by moderate Islamists to hold
talks with the military-backed government.
</P>
<P>
"It is not blind violence... but is opposing the start of
dialogue between the Algerian government and certain legalistic
Islamists who will take away the fruits (from the militants)," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine was referring to less extreme groups of Islamic
fundamentalists in Algeria, including the former Islamic Salvation
Front, who want to talk with the government to seek a political
solution.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of people were massacred over the past few weeks by
Islamic militants in villages near Algiers, in what was the worst
wave of violence against civilians since Algeria was plunged into
a civil war five years ago.
</P>
<P>
The fresh outbreak of atrocities against civilians has drawn
worldwide attention and made the United Nations Secretary General
Kofi Annan appeal to the Algerian government to seek a political,
rather than military, solution to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine said that the present situation in Algeria is similar
to that of 1962, when the French colonial government was forced to
withdraw from Algeria by guerrillas who waged an eight-year war of
terror.
</P>
<P>
"The present war is extremely cruel. Our task is to prepare for
the post-war period (of Algeria)," he said.
</P>
<P>
The daily Liberation said that a human rights committee
attached to the French government will issue a resolution today on
the crisis in Algeria.
</P>
<P>
This will be the first time for the French government to break
its silence over Algeria for years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
