<HEADLINE> 38 LRA Rebels Killed in Uganda in Last Two Weeks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan rebel, Lord's
Resistance Army (LRA), lost 38 fighters in battles with the
Uganda army in last two weeks, ''The New Vision'' reported today.
</P>
<P>
During the fighting between August 26 and September 8, the
Uganda army captured from the rebels 63 rifles, one 82 mm
recoilless gun, two rocket propelled grenades, one anti-tank mine
and over 400 rounds of ammunitions, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Yesterday, the army shelled for about 12 hours a suspected
rebel hideout in Atto hills in the northern Kitgum District. The
result of the shelling is not available when the report was sent.
</P>
<P>
The rebels are under constant pressure from the army and they
have also fallen into acute food shortage.
</P>
<P>
LRA, based in southern Sudan, has been haunting in northern
Ugandan districts of Gulu and Kitgum. Its fighters have
reportedly decreased from thousands to some 450 at present. 
</P>
