<HEADLINE> C'wealth Ministerial Group to Make Decisions on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Commonwealth Ministerial
Action Group (CMAG) will start a two-day meeting in London today
to decide its relation with Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will produce CMAG's final report to the
commonwealth summit in Edinburgh, Scotland, in October.
</P>
<P>
Though there is pressure to expel Nigeria from the
organization, reports said it is more likely that Nigeria's
suspension two years ago will continue.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Secretary-General Emeka Anyaoku denied earlier
that there is a plan to expel Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
When it was suspended from the commonwealth in November 1995
for executing author Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight other Ogoni
activists, Nigeria was given a two-year ultimatum to improve its
human rights records.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria insists that the Ogoni nine was executed for murder in
accordance with the lawful procedure. It accuses the Commonwealth
of interfering in its internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria also argues that it has since made great progress. A
national human rights commission has been established to handle
with various human rights abuses, the transition to civil rule
program is going well.
</P>
<P>
But some commonwealth nations, especially Canada and the new
British government do not seem satisfied and are taking tough
positions on the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
