<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Join Information Super Highway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria is set to join the
Information Super Highway this December, with the installation of
a 15-million-U.S.-Dollar national internet gateway with a
two-megabit capacity.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Champion newspaper reported today that Nigeria has
signed an agreement with the United Nations Development Program
(UNDP) which qualifies it to benefit from the latter's Internet
Initiative for Africa (IIA).
</P>
<P>
IIA aims to provide internet gateway for 10 to 12 African
countries.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, UNDP will grant 500,000 Dollars to
Nigeria for the installation of a fully functioning internet
gateway as well as related training and domain name registration.
</P>
<P>
After signing the agreement last week, Communications Minister
Tajudeen Olanrewaju reportedly said that he was happy that the
country's awareness and understanding of internet has improved
tremendously.
</P>
<P>
A report said Gambia has also been approved as a beneficiary
of IIA, while talks are still on concerning Sao Tome &AMP; Principe,
Burkina Faso, Congo, Central African Republic and Cape Verde.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
