<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Upgrade Agricultural Training </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Training programs are being
upgraded at Zimbabwe's colleges and institutes to equip
agricultural students adequately to face future challenges,
Lands and Agriculture Minister Kumbirai Kangai said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Responding to issues and concerns raised by parliament members
during the debate on the presidential motion, Kangai said the
rapid technological advances made in the agricultural industry
demanded a high calibre of extension staff to be trained at
agricultural training institutions.
</P>
<P>
Certificate training is being phased out and all eligible
certificate holders in AGRITEX, Department of Research and
Specialist Services, veterinary services, and agricultural
education will undergo modular training to upgrade them to
diploma level, he said.
</P>
<P>
The lowest level extension agent will hold a diploma, while
higher national diploma courses will be offered at Chibero and
Gwebi Colleges of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Kangai said AGRITEX had decentralized to districts and wards
to become more responsive to service users, but mobility was
being severely hampered by inadequate transport facilities.
</P>
<P>
There are about 1.2 million individual farm families in
Zimbabwe to be visited by extension staff. 
</P>
</TEXT>
