<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German FM Protests Croats' Boycott of Local Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 11 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus
Kinkel today strongly protested Croats' decision to boycott the
Bosnian local elections scheduled for the coming weekend.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Thursday in Bonn, Kinkel called the
boycott decision made by the Croatian Democratic Union "absolutely
unacceptable".
</P>
<P>
It was even more incomprehensible especially after the Serb
leadership in Pale apparently had approved their participation in
the elections Wednesday evening, Kinkel added.
</P>
<P>
The Croatian Democratic Union decided last Tuesday that Bosnian
Croats would "refuse to participate in local elections," because
conditions were not yet ripe in Bosnia to hold them.
</P>
<P>
The union claimed that holding Bosnian elections violates
articles of the Dayton agreement and electoral program, and thus
also violates the interests of Croats.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel, however, stressed that the elections must be held in
order to ensure adherence to the Dayton peace accord.
</P>
<P>
He noted that he could hardly believe that "with the elections
only a few days away, it is the Croat side which has become the
political block to the political coexistence of different ethnic
groups in Bosnia on the basis of democratic elections."
</P>
<P>
He called on Croats' leaders to lift the boycott, threatening
that international financial aid to them could be stopped if they
denied the call.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel also confirmed that he and his British counterpart Robin
Cook had issued a joint letter to the Croat member of the Bosnian
presidency, Kresimir Zubak, to protest the latest event.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Croats' boycott was caused by the
poorly-distributed power in Bosnia. In the Moslem-Croat region of
Mostar, Delwald and Zepa, Moslems are the majority, so the Croats
fear that they would not get a relevant majority in the
elections.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
