<HEADLINE> DPRK Soldier Repatriated Through Panmunjom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 11 (Xinhua) -- South Korea repatriated a
soldier of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK)
through the truce village of Panmunjom at 10:30 Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean government said that it was returning Cho
Kang-won, 22, under the South-North Korean Basic Agreement.
</P>
<P>
Cho, found on the small island of Kyodong-do in the Yellow Sea
on August 25, said that he accidentally fell into the Yesong River
from a small boat and asked to return home, the Defense Ministry
said.
</P>
<P>
During the interrogations, Cho initially expressed an intention
to defect to the South, but soon reversed his decision. After
reviewing his case, the government concluded that he merely
drifted here and had no intention to defect, said the ministry
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
South Korea has several times repatriated DPRK's soldiers who
had accidentally drifted into southern waters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
