<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 09:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNRWA to Maintain Austere Despite New Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Relief Works
Agency (UNRWA) will maintain some austerity measures despite
pledges of fresh fundings from some donor countries, local media
reported today.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement released here Wednesday night by UNRWA's
Cairo office, Commissioner Peter Hansen said it canceled the
controversial school fees but will keep in place a cut of
international staff and freeze of recruitment of teachers.
</P>
<P>
This came at last as a relief to the worrying and angry
Palestinians. The U.N. organ, which is in charge of helping more
than some 3 million Palestinian refugees in Jordan, Syria,
Lebanon, the West Bank and Gaza Strip, had announced it faced a 20
million dollars deficit for fiscal year 1997.
</P>
<P>
It planned last month to charge tuition fees for school
children in Gaza Strip for the first time in nearly half a century
since the massive fleeing of Palestinians in 1948 following the
creation of Israel.
</P>
<P>
The projected austerity measures also included freezing
appointment of teachers and reducing hospitalization programs and
medical treatment services. Those had triggered widespread protest
from Palestinians and criticism from the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday donor nations gathered in Amman, capital of Jordan,
to try to plug the shortfall in the UNRWA budget. Japan pledged to
contribute 12.6 million dollars while the U.S. agreed to offer 7.5
million dollars, including 1.5 million dollars for refugees in
Lebanon. The Netherlands and Germany also promised to pay 1
million each.
</P>
<P>
UNRWA offered free support to the Palestinians over the past
half century. However, it says it faces an impossible task trying
to maintain services to a population of refugees growing at 3.8
percent a year while donations have not grown since 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
