<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's New Trades Growing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Terms like assessor, auditor,
or advertiser used to be foreign words to ordinary Chinese but
they're becoming much more popular these days.
</P>
<P>
The reforms and opening up that started in the late 1970s have
brought about a shift from the centrally-planned economy to a
market economy. Therefore, these new services have emerged to meet
the needs of a changing society.
</P>
<P>
Appraisal of assets came into being in the late '80s at a time
when China was reforming its state property management system, but
it's now involved in almost every aspect of business.
</P>
<P>
The country had 3,343 appraisers, with 55,000 employees, by the
end of last year, and business has spread to the non-governmental
sector.
</P>
<P>
Advertising has become a major means of enterprises to attract
customers. In 1996, the sector did some 36 billion yuan in
business, and there were more than 52,000 agencies with 510,000
staff members.
</P>
<P>
Other newly-emerging businesses include information services,
consulting, market surveys, computer applications, leasing,
entertainment, and accounting, legal advice, and auditing.
</P>
<P>
Electronic information industry has been listed as a pillar
industry in 24 provinces, autonomous regions, and municipalities,
according to Wu Jiapei, an expert at the State Information Center.
</P>
<P>
China now has more than 20,000 businesses engaged in
information services, with some 400,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
However, not all the new businesses are doing well. The market
study business, for example, began in 1986 with four small private
institutions doing surveys. Now, there are more than 400
organizations, but they have trouble with the low market demand.
</P>
<P>
The new businesses may have good prospects though, because more
regulations, laws and standardized practices are being adopted to
guide their development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
