<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Court of Final Appeal Handles First Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Court of Final Appeal
(CFA) of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) today
held hearings on an application for an appeal of a criminal case.
</P>
<P>
It is the first case that the CFA handled after it was
established on July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Chief Justice of the CFA Andrew Li and two permanent judges
Henry Denis Litton and Charles Arthur Ching formed an appeal
committee for the case.
</P>
<P>
The case involved a young woman who was adjudicated by a local
court on her beating other people early this year. She lodged her
application for appeal to the CFA.
</P>
<P>
After the hearing, Andrew Li announced that the appeal
committee would not grant leave to the application of the appeal.
</P>
<P>
The CFA is the highest appellate court in the HKSAR and it
hears appeals on civil and criminal matters from the High Court,
the Court of Appeal and the Court of First Instance.
</P>
<P>
Before July 1 this year, it was only the Privy Council of
Britain that had the final say to the appeals from Hong Kong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
