<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Offer Better Terms for Foreign High-Tech Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 11 (Xinhua) -- China is expected to offer
more preferential policies to foreign-funded high-tech firms in
China in order to further boost foreign investment in the field.
</P>
<P>
Preferential policies will cover taxes levied on the import of
equipment by foreign-backed high-tech firms.
</P>
<P>
Sun Zhenyu, vice-minister of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation, made the remarks in an interview with newsmen during
China's on-going first investment and trade fair in Xiamen,
capital of southeast coastal province of Fujian.
</P>
<P>
Sun added that China will gradually introduce national
treatment for overseas-funded firms.
</P>
<P>
Since the introduction of the reform and opening policies,
China has offered a series of preferential terms for foreign
companies, including tax exemptions for imported equipment.
</P>
<P>
On April 1, 1996, China readjusted its taxation policy and
canceled the tax exemption policy for equipment imported by
foreign-funded firms.
</P>
<P>
Sun said that further improvements in investment environment
will include readjusted customs duties, income taxes and some
standard charges, as well as the gradual introduction of national
treatment for foreign-funded firms.
</P>
<P>
He noted that national treatment for foreign-funded firms is in
line with international norms and the fair competition principle
of the market economy. The final goal is to ensure that domestic
and foreign firms compete on an equal footing and share common
development, Sun said.
</P>
<P>
Sun went on to say that China is considering readjustments in
customs duties applicable to foreign-funded firms in order to
boost foreign investment in the high-tech sector.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that high-tech firms require a wide range of
imported advanced equipment, and that current customs duties and
value-added taxes will account 40 percent of the total value of
imported equipment, thus adding a great deal to production costs
and in turn affect the international competitiveness of related
firms.
</P>
<P>
China is therefore considering the introduction of more
preferential terms for foreign-backed hi-tech firms in order to
improve quality in the use of foreign investment and establish
more high-tech projects, according to Sun.
</P>
<P>
In June 1995, China issued a number of temporary regulations
guiding foreign investment and a directory for foreign-funded
industries to encourage foreign investors to place their money in
high-tech industries, infrastructure and agricultural
areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
