<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast China Book Fair Shows Buyer Interest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, September 11 (Xinhua) -- In spite of the record
business at a recent national book fair, people in the publishing
industry are worried about Chinese reading habits - or lack of
them.
</P>
<P>
The book fair last week in the city of Changchun in northeast
China's Jilin province set two records: 509 million yuan (about 63
million US dollars) in book orders, and 32 million yuan in sales.
</P>
<P>
But, half the orders and sales were for children's books,
textbooks, or reference books for school students. The traditional
emphasis on education among Chinese has remained in recent years,
according to Xue Youzhi, teacher of Jilin University. The problem
is that they seem to put too much stress on exam results, and not
enough on how they form their personalities and value judgements,
he added.
</P>
<P>
One survey done at the fair put education books at the top of
the best-seller list, followed by children's books, social
sciences, reference works, and literature. Books on science and
technology, including popular science, came in sixth.
</P>
<P>
Total book sales in China have averaged some five billion yuan
annually for the past several years, indicating that the Chinese
in general spend very little on books, about 4.1 yuan per person
each year, industry people note.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that per-capita spending on books in 1996
remained at about the same level as ten years ago, if not lower by
a bit. They point out that sales and orders of literary works are
mostly for classic novels and that the number of novels published
in recent years is declining.
</P>
<P>
But, books directed at rural readers are still welcome - to
publishers' great relief. One set of books intended for farmers,
for example, resulted in 680,000 orders.
</P>
<P>
An official with the State Press and Publication Administration
says that, as a whole, a great number of the Chinese just have not
formed good reading habits, and "changing that situation takes
time and will require a concerted effort - including holding more
book fairs." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
