<HEADLINE> LTTE Hands Over Bodies of Sailors to ICRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan Tamil rebels have
handed over the bodies of four ship crew members or army soldiers
killed in Tuesday's pre-dawn attack against a Chinese vessel off
Pulmoddai coast in Trincomalee District, local newspapers said
today.
</P>
<P>
The Sinhalese newspaper, Daily News, reported that the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) handed over the remains to
the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
But it is still not clear whether there are any Chinese killed
in the attack or not.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-two Chinese crew members were on board the vessel at the
time of the attack.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Embassy in Sri Lanka on Wednesday sent two
diplomats to Pulmoddai to carry out investigations. They had met
senior army and navy officers in the region to discuss the
situation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, at a press conference held this morning at the Sri
Lankan Parliament, a military spokesman said that five Chinese
crew members were still missing. He made no mention of the
casualties suffered by the Chinese crew.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said there were 31 Chinese on board the cargo
and eight of them were missing.
</P>
<P>
The engine room of the cargo, the MV Cordiality, was seriously
damaged after the rebels fired several rounds of rocket-propelled
grenades to it. However, troops managed to save the ship as well
as its cargo of ilmenite after they repulsed the fierce attack by
the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
Initial reports put the death toll of both sides at 32, with
many people missing.
</P>
<P>
The 200-meter long MV Cordiality is the biggest foreign vessel
so far attacked by LTTE, shipping sources said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
