<HEADLINE> Kenya Supports Sanctions Against Burundi: Moi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Kenya supports the continued
sanctions against Burundi military regime imposed by an
extraordinary regional summit held last Thursday in Dar es
Salaam, Tanzania, the Daily Nation today quoted Kenyan President
Daniel arap Moi as saying.
</P>
<P>
Moi asked a private Kenyan airline to stop its flights to
Burundi immediately, adding that African Airline International
(AAI) should respect the decision of the regional summit.
</P>
<P>
But Moi said, while Addressing a mass rally Wednesday in
Western Province, that Kenya had decided to lift the oil embargo
to Burundi and recently allowed Burundi to import limited amounts
of fuel.
</P>
<P>
The decision to allow oil import to Burundi, he said, was
intended to benefit ordinary citizens who were feeling the pinch
of the sanctions, he added.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Tanzanian government banned AAI from overflying
its airspace because the Kenyan airline had made flights to
Burundi in violation of the regional sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The extraordinary summit which Moi failed to attend pledged to
continue regional sanctions against Burundi implemented in July
1996 after Pierre Buyoya seized power in a coup.
</P>
<P>
The summit also agreed to seek a global oil and arms embargo
against the central African nation, to press for the severance of
diplomatic relations worldwide and move for seizure of all
Burundi government assets abroad.
</P>
<P>
Julius Nyerere, facilitator of the Burundi peace process and
former Tanzanian President, is expected to convene another summit
in Arusha, northern Tanzania, before the end of September.
</P>
</TEXT>
