<HEADLINE> Overseas Funding for Reform of State-Owned Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Liaoning
Province, a major heavy industrial center in the country, plans to
utilize four billion US dollars in foreign funds over the next
three year to upgrade 300 major state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Speaking yesterday at the China Investment and Trade Fair in
session in this port city, Assistant Governor of Liaoning Province
Yang Baoshan said that Liaoning, northeast China's only coastal
province, is ready to offer flexible cooperative terms to overseas
business partners.
</P>
<P>
He said overseas business people are being encouraged to
establish joint ventures with local enterprises, which will
provide investment in the form of fixed assets.
</P>
<P>
He also invited foreign governments and financial institutions
to provide loans for upgrading existing enterprises. Efficient
enterprises with bright market prospects will be selected for
listings on overseas stock markets.
</P>
<P>
Through international bidding, a number of major state-owned
enterprises will be leased or operated by overseas consortiums and
businesses, he added.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning is currently home to more than 15,000 foreign-funded
enterprises, with contracted foreign investments of 23.7 billion
US dollars. Some 6,500 of said firms are currently in operation.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning's more than 1,300 medium- and large enterprises
account for 10 percent of the national total.
</P>
<P>
The State Council, China's highest administrative body, has
prioritized Liaoning's 163 technological upgrading projects, with
investment totaling 48.3 billion yuan.  
</P>
