<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Diversion Project in Tengger Desert Going Smoothly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, September 11 (Xinhua) -- More than 800 workers are
currently working full bore to complete second phase construction
of a water diversion project crossing the Tengger Desert in
northwest China.
</P>
<P>
Second phase construction of the Jingtaichuan water diversion
channel, which is designed to divert water from Yellow River to a
reservoir in Minqin County, Gansu Province, will be the first
Chinese project of its kind to cross a desert.
</P>
<P>
The project will also provide a guaranteed water supply for
irrigating 40,000 hectares of farmland in Minqin, located in the
northeastern part of Gansu Corridor which has suffered severe
water shortage.
</P>
<P>
The second phase, which will be completed at an estimated cost
of 246 million yuan, will require the construction of a channel
stretching 101.44 km and replacing 30 pieces of equipment at 13
pump stations along the main canal. The annual water diversion
volume will hit 61 million cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
Construction commenced in November 1995 and the project is
scheduled for completion in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Tengger Desert covers more than 40,000 sq.km. at the
juncture of Gansu Province and the Ningxia Hui and Inner Mongolia
autonomous regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Minister Concerned About Trade-Environment Linkage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Thai Agriculture and
Cooperatives Minister Chucheep Hansawat today voiced Thailand's
concern that environment and conservation issues are being
increasingly related to trade.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening session of a two-day meeting of ASEAN
ministers of agriculture and forestry (AMAF) in Bangkok, Chucheep
said AMAF needs to demonstrate both the political will and
commitment to ensure that emerging issues and challenges are
addressed in an effective and timely manner.
</P>
<P>
He said AMAF's commitment should include the ability to require
national government bodies to accelerate their work on key issues
arising from the trade liberalization process.
</P>
<P>
A key issue is its ability to meet increasingly high and more
strictly enforced sanitary standards, which are frequently used as
indirect barriers to trade, he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged members of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) to pay greater attention to the potential impacts of the
meetings and agreements which are designed to 'strengthen the
linkages between trade and the environment."
</P>
<P>
The deliberations and consultations, he added, may affect trade
in ASEAN's agricultural products, and Thailand is presently facing
the problem in shrimp exports.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the meeting will come to a consensus
on a new agenda and new directions for AMAF, including the
development of more efficient operational mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
Ministers from all nine ASEAN members are attending the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Environmental groups in the world have accused the shrimp
industry of destroying mangrove forests and the coastal
environment, while the United States is demanding that a turtle
excluder device be attached to the trawler net to allow turtles to
escape if caught. Thailand's exports of shrimp have dropped as a
result of these accusations and demands.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
