<HEADLINE> Iran Urges France to Stop Israeli Aggression </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Iran urged France to use its
influence as the head of the ceasefire monitoring committee to
stop current Israeli aggression on Lebanon, Iran's official news
agency IRNA reported today.
</P>
<P>
The call was made by Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi
in a telephone conversation with his French counterpart Hubert
Vedrine Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to IRNA, the two ministers discussed the latest
developments in the Middle East and Israel's "new incursions and
transgression against the south Lebanese soil."
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi expressed concern over the Israeli breach of the
ceasefire and its continuation of aggression on Lebanon,
stressing that the Israeli violation would further aggravate the
Middle East crisis.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine on his part described the regional situation as
dangerous and said that he had made contacts with both parties
and appealed for their restraint from violating the ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
The ceasefire agreement, which was reached in April 1996
between Israel and Lebanon, bars the fighting sides from targeting
civilians.
</P>
<P>
The ceasefire monitoring committee consists of representatives
of Lebanon, Syria, Israel, France and the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
