<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Environmental Policy Implemented in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 11 (Xinhua) -- A new policy demanding
Environmental Impact Assessments (EIA) before development can
occur in certain areas in Zimbabwe came into force this week, the
daily newspaper The Herald reported today.
</P>
<P>
The policy document was released here Wednesday at a workshop
on environmental management.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from government and non-government organizations as
well as environmental experts attended the three-day workshop
which started on September 9.
</P>
<P>
Development which is likely to cause serious environmental
damage are well planned by the developers and approved by the
Ministry of Mines, Environme nt and Tourism before work begins,
according to the document.
</P>
<P>
The policy applies to electricity generation and transmission
lines, water supply, oil or gas exploration, housing or
industrial developments, mining, waste treatment and disposal,
road, rail or airport facilities and other projects that can
cause damage.
</P>
<P>
Officers from the Ministry of Mines, Environment and Tourism
said provisions for fines would be included in revised versions
of the document. It was important to value the cost of the piece
of affected environment before fines could be worked out, they noted.
</P>
<P>
The document stresses that developers are required to consider
all aspects of the project they intend to carry out and discuss
the work with relevant authorities and the affected parties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Electronic Pet Makes Children Feel Lonely: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Playing with electronic pets
can be a cause of loneliness in children, says Sun Yunxiao, deputy
director of the Chinese Youth Research Center.
</P>
<P>
It can create obstacles to developing normal relationships with
others because it is merely a dialogue with a machine, Sun
explains, adding that playing with electronic pets alienates
children from their schoolmates and others.
</P>
<P>
Many children, especially those from one-child families, regard
electronic pets as a means of avoiding difficulties in study and
social activities, but that can lead to an inward-looking
personality.
</P>
<P>
Children who are obsessed with the pets usually care less about
others and are more likely to get angry over minor conflicts and
look for ways to get revenge, Sun says, suggesting that parents
encourage children to make friends with each other instead of with
machines.
</P>
<P>
China's State Education Commission has banned students from
carrying electronic pets to class.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
