<HEADLINE> South Korean Economic Foundation Remains Sound: Kim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 11 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim
Young-sam today downplayed fears of the end of the nation's
economic miracle.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously, South Korean economy is currently experiencing some
difficulties as it undergoes a period of structural
transformation; nevertheless, the foundation remains sound," he
said in an address at the second-day session of the Korea Summit
in downtown Seoul.
</P>
<P>
"The government is consistently easing regulations and pursuing
a policy of reform to facilitate industrial restructuring," he
added.
</P>
<P>
"The difficulties that the South Korean economy is undergoing
will serve as a positive impetus for industrial restructuring and
enhancing competitiveness. The government places major emphasis on
encouraging competition, expanding openness and reforming various
regulations to more actively promote a market economy," said the
president.
</P>
<P>
"South Korea's experience, coupled with these efforts, I firmly
believe, will contribute to the development of the world economy
and warrants an optimistic outlook for our economy," he said.
