<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Archives Opens Historical Files </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai Archives
recently opened more than 190,000 precious historical files dating
from the Republic of China (1912-1949) and the early period of the
People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
The archives welcomes people from all walks of life to view the
files, said director Zhang Gan, adding that overseas parties can
also gain access to the files by applying with the archives at
least one month in advance.
</P>
<P>
The archives has opened 530,000 of 1.65 million files in its
collections.
</P>
<P>
The most recent files opened to public record Shanghai's
political, economic, cultural and social history since the
beginning of this century.
</P>
<P>
Many of the judicial files, dating to the 1912-1949 period, are
valuable historical documents which will promote studies of the
judicial systems and legal history of the Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
Experts note that financial documents from more than 60 banks
and related subsidiary firms in the city will be extremely
valuable for research into the financial history during the
1912-1949 period.
</P>
<P>
In addition, over 4,000 files covering administrative
management, communications and law enforcement will be valuable
for research related to the history of the concession.
</P>
<P>
The 50,000 files recently opened cover the period between
1949-1966 and offer detailed accounts of the situation surrounding
Shanghai's economic and cultural development since the
establishment of the People's Republic of China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Courses In Psychology For High School Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai will provide
psychology courses for all students in its 3,000 primary and high
schools by the year 2000, in an effort to help them cope with some
psychological problems.
</P>
<P>
Specialists will provide guidance for the students in China's
biggest commercial and trade center, which is becoming embarrassed
by the problems that more and more youngsters are having. Many
students say they feel depressed and under a heavy amount of
pressure. What is worse, the number of suicides has been on the
rise since the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Experts attribute the situation to the fierce competition for
places at university and to the complexity of modern life. And,
the traditional methods used by Chinese schools and families have
not proven very ineffective in dealing with the problems.
</P>
<P>
To help the students with their psychological well-being is a
major job for Shanghai's educators, so psychologists have been
hired for some 800 schools in the past several years, and special
textbooks have been prepared. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xi'an Establishes Talent Exchange Information Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Xi'an, capital of northwest
China's Shaanxi Province, recently established a talent exchange
information network.
</P>
<P>
The network supplies the Xi'an Talent Market (XTM), the largest
organization of its kind in northwest China, with information on
123,000 people. The market helped over 11,000 people find new jobs
in its first year of operations.
</P>
<P>
XTM Deputy-Director Luo Kaiwen noted that Shaanxi is home to
more than 50 colleges and universities, but most graduates prefer
to work in developed coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
The network helps local enterprises attract experienced
technicians from across the nation and in the process has handled
over 20,000 inquiries via links with other networks across the
country, according to Luo.
</P>
<P>
"The market has installed 14 special phone lines to serve
job-hunters", said Luo, adding the XTM will join Internet next
year in order to provide people with an opportunity to search for
jobs worldwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
