<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investment in West China Beating That in The East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Investment in the western
parts of China is 10.9 percentage points more than in the east
this year, a sign that the central government's attempt to narrow
the east-west gap is beginning to pay off.
</P>
<P>
In the first seven months, the west had 86.7 billion yuan in
investment, a year-on-year increase of 19.9 percent, compared with
a nine-percent increase for the east, according to Prof. Zhang
Hanya of the State Planning Commission's Investment Research
Institute.
</P>
<P>
At the start of the Ninth Five-Year Plan, China has intensified
economic development in relatively poor western parts, which have
been given priority in project approval and fund allocation.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, investment in the western was far behind that of the
east, but last year the gap began to close. It is not expected to
widen within this century, and will be gradually narrowed at the
beginning of the the next century.
</P>
<P>
In the first seven months of this year, state projects
accounted for 41 percent of the total spending on western areas,
but 59 percent came from the west itself, indicating greater
independence in development.
</P>
<P>
Ministries have also increased spending on infrastructure in
western areas. The Nanning-Kunming Railway line in southwest
China, which is partly open to traffic, will be electrified by the
end of this year. The 976-km extension project of the Southern
Xinjiang Railway line will be completed in 1999, ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan plans to spend 23.5 billion yuan on 58 key projects
this year. And a project for a cotton base in Xinjiang has begun,
with more than nine billion yuan in investment expected. The
region will produce 1.2 million tons of cotton by the end of the
century.
</P>
<P>
China's strategy to speed up economic growth in the west has
helped the area a lot, and the resource-rich west will be a new
economic growth area, economists say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
