<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Seeded Players Upset at U.S. Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Defending world
champion Dong Jiong of China, along with another two of the
world's top ten singles players, were upset in the third round of
the U.S. Open Badminton Championships on Wednesday at the Orange
County Badminton Club.
</P>
<P>
Dong Jiong, the world's second-ranked player and the
tournament's top seed, was stopped by 16th-rated Alan Budi Kusuma
of Indonesia, 15-13 18-13.
</P>
<P>
Third-seeded Peter Rasmussen of Denmark, ranked fifth
in the world, conceded a 4-15, 15-6, 15-7 loss to 24th-ranked
Jeroen van Dijk from the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Fourth-seeded Ardy Wiranta of Indonesia, seventh in the world
rankings, fell to China's 18th-rated Luo Yigang 5-15 15-10 15-7.
</P>
<P>
Denmark's Poul-Erik Hoyer-Larsen was the only player among the
top four seeds to reach Thursday's quarter-finals. The
second-seeded Hoyer-Larsen, ranked fourth in the world, will play
Indonesia's Marleve Mainaky who beat China's Chen Gang 6-15, 15-7,
15-10. 
</P>
</TEXT>
