<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama Unveils New Plan on Canal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Panama decided to set up
an agency to deal with maritime and fishery matters at the
end of an international conference on the Panama Canal.
</P>
<P>
In its 21st century-oriented shipping plan, Panama also decided
to develop new infrastructure -- inter-oceanic ports and railroads
-- to make itself a center of multi-model transportation.
</P>
<P>
Maritime companies and institutions from more than 40 countries
and regions gathered for the three-day conference, known as
"Universal Congress on Panama Canal" and intended to prepare for
the return of the canal's sovereignty to Panama at the end of this
century.
</P>
<P>
"We will create the Maritime Agency of Panama (MAP) which would
be in charge to fulfill the numerous international agreements
already ratified by Panama on maritime and fishery issues,"
Panama's Minister of the Presidency Olmedo Miranda said today.
</P>
<P>
Miranda said one of the purposes of MAP will be to improve the
industrial activities in the canal in order to attract new clients
from all around the world.
</P>
<P>
The official said Panama`s project to improve the canal`s
performance is based on the United Nation Agreement on Maritime
Laws.
</P>
<P>
MAP will also support development of maritime industry through
taxation incentives, technical aid and market information.
</P>
<P>
"The latter includes tourism, primarily cruise tourism,
establishing seafood processing plants, and creating centers of
stock and distribution of merchandise," he said.
</P>
<P>
Miranda pointed out Panama is fixing an alternating
infrastructure to serve ships crossing the canal, like port usage,
technical maintenance, as well as the construction of a regional
railroad.
</P>
<P>
According to treaties signed by the governments of Panama and
the United States in 1977, the United States must deliver control
of the canal to Panama and withdraw all its troops from the canal
district no later than December 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations and China did not participate in the
conference because Panama invited Lee Teng-hui, leader of the
Taiwan authorities, to the conference.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters on August 21, Brandt Juan Carlos,
associate spokesman for the U.N. secretary general, said, "The
U.N. has decided not to participate in the conference due to the
fact that if we do, we will be in a certain way violating another
General Assembly resolution that recognizes the People's Republic
of China as the sole representative of China in the United
Nations."
</P>
<P>
On September 9, China expressed regret over Panama's decision
to invite Taiwan authorities to the conference. "The Panamanian
government has disregarded China's solemn statements and
admonitions, and has acted in violation of the U.N. Charter and
U.N. Resolution 2758," Chinese Foreign Ministry Spokesman Shen
Guofang told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Top leaders of some Western countries also did not attend the
meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
