<HEADLINE> Georgia-- Abkhazia Conflict May be Resolved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The Republic of Georgia and
its autonomous Republic of Abkhazia are expected to sign a joint
memorandum on the complete resolution of conflicts between the two
sides, in Moscow soon.
</P>
<P>
This was announced in a joint communique issued today after
two-day talks held in the Abkhazian capital of Sukhumi.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Itar-Tass news agency and Interfax said the two
sides mainly discussed issues of refugee repatriation and joint
efforts to fight terrorism in warring territories.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from the United Nations and Russia also attended the
talks.
</P>
<P>
Abkhazia is an autonomous republic of Georgia. It declared
independence from Georgia in February, 1992. Armed conflict
between Georgian government troops and local forces followed in
Sukhumi in August the same year.
</P>
<P>
A ceasefire agreement was signed under mediation by the United
Nations and Russia in May 1994.
</P>
<P>
Georgian President Shevardnadze and Abkhazian President
Ardzinba agreed to resolve the conflicts by political means after
their first meeting on August 15. However, the issue of Abkhazia's
status is still suspended.  
</P>
</TEXT>
