<HEADLINE> U.S. to Support SAARC Process: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government is
seeking ways to support the SAARC process including the
establishment of South Asian Free Trade Area by 2001, said
visiting U.S. Assistant Secretary of State for South Asian Affairs
Karl F. Inderfurth.
</P>
<P>
Inderfurth made the remark Wednesday at the airport after
concluding a two-day visit to Nepal.
</P>
<P>
"From our experience with North American Free Trade Area, we
can offer some technical advice on how one goes about creating a
free trade area," he was quoted as saying by Nepali newspapers
published today.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Nepal, Inderfurth met Naeem U. Hasan,
secretary general of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC), which groups Nepal, Bhutan, India, Sri Lanka,
Bangladesh, Pakistan and the Maldives.
</P>
<P>
He also met Nepali Prime Minister Lokendra Bahadur Chand and
Foreign Minister Kamal Thapa.
</P>
<P>
If properly harnessed, Nepal's water resources will help boost
not only Nepal's economy but that of the entire region, Inderfurth
also said before departing for Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Nepal has a huge hydroelectric potential of 83 million kw, but
less than one percent has been utilized so far.
</P>
<P>
Inderfurth, who assumed his current post in April, is on a
"familiarization tour" in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
He has visited India, Pakistan and Nepal. His last leg is Sri
Lanka.  
</P>
</TEXT>
