<HEADLINE> Communication Minister asked by His Party to Quit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Communication Minister Anwar
Hossain, who is also the Secretary General of Bangladesh's third
largest Jatiya (national) Party (JP), was asked by his Party boss
HM Ershad to quit his post in the Cabinet, local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The JP Chairman, who acted as President of Bangladesh in 1980s,
told local news agency UNB that he had asked Manju to relinquish
the ministerial job and work full time for reactivating the JP,
which is beset with party split and lower morale.
</P>
<P>
"I advised him to think over the matter as I badly need him as
full-time secretary general for the interest of the party," said
Ershad, whose party lent support to Awami (people's) League in
forming government after last year's election.
</P>
<P>
Praising Manju for his sacrifice and contribution to the JP as
well as his organizational capacity, Ershad said he is a very
conscientious man and would certainly understand the present
reality.
</P>
<P>
The JP Chairman said his party workers and sympathizers
frequently questioned him about the dual position of JP as the
party secretary general remains in the government.
</P>
<P>
Claiming his party as a responsible opposition, the JP supremo
said: "We have never supported this government. Our stand is
clear: Support the good work and oppose the wrongdoing of the
government."
</P>
<P>
The JP leader also rejected the notion of mid-term election
proposed by the largest opposition Bangladesh Nationalist Party,
saying the government should be allowed to complete its full
five-year term.
</P>
<P>
However, "if the government continues to prove failure on all
fronts and people get fed up with its rule, then the situation
might be different," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
