<HEADLINE> Costa Rica to Strengthen Protection of Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, September 10 (Xinhua) -- A plan aimed to prevent
child labor from emerging will be implemented in Costa Rica by
governmental and non-governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
Labor Minister Farid Ayales said here today that the
implementation of the plan would guarantee education for children
and reduce school drop-outs.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the international rules to which Costa Rica
has been subscribed, the government is also looking forward to
launching a legislative reform to set 15 years old as the least
age for work, Ayales said.
</P>
<P>
According to UNICEF, about 120,000 minors aged from five to 17
work in Costa Rica, and half of them are under 15 years old.
</P>
<P>
Prostitution is another social problem which threatens children
and youths, Ayales said. It is estimated that there are 2,000 girl
prostitutes in Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
Officials and social institutions are worried about tourism
advertisements which offer sex-tours in Costa Rica for foreigners
and called for checking this sort of tourism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
