<HEADLINE> Britain, Germany Protest Croats' Boycott </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, September 10 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Minister Robin
Cook and his German counterpart, Klaus Kinkel, here today jointly
protested to Croats' boycotting the Bosnian local elections
scheduled for the coming weekend.
</P>
<P>
In a joint letter to the Croat member of the Bosnian
presidency, Kresimir Zubak, they expressed their regret at the
action of the Croatian Democratic Union (Hrvatska Demokratska
Zajednica), which claims "to protect the Bosnian Croats' vital
interests."
</P>
<P>
The letter was delivered to Zubak by ambassadors.
</P>
<P>
The Croatian Democratic Union decided last Tuesday that Bosnian
Croats would "refuse to participate in local elections," because
conditions were not yet ripe in Bosnia to hold them.
</P>
<P>
The union claims that holding Bosnian elections violates
articles of the Dayton agreement and electoral program, and thus
also violates the interests of Croats.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Croats' boycott was caused by the
poorly-distributed power in Bosnia. In the Moslem-Croat region of
Mostar, Delwald and Zepa, Moslems are the majority, so the Croats
fear that they would not get a relevant majority in the
elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
