<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank OKs Debt Relief Package for Bolivia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has agreed
to help relieve Bolivia's foreign debt and refocus the country's
resources on economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
The effort, said the bank today, is part of a package agreed on
together with the International Monetary Fund (IMF) to reduce
Bolivia's public debt by some 448 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The package is equivalent to about one-seventh of the recipient
nation's total external debt in what the bank called Net Present
Value (NPV) terms, the international lending agency said.
</P>
<P>
The deal, of which the World Bank has pledged some 54 million
dollars, is subject to confirmation of the other creditors of
Bolivia that they will provide their share of the debt reduction.
</P>
<P>
Over time, said the bank headquartered here, the 448 million
dollars NPV reduction is equivalent to a cumulative debt service
reduction of 600 million dollars in nominal dollar terms.
</P>
<P>
It is expected to cut the debt of Bolivia, the second after
Uganda to benefit from such a program, to a sustainable level, and
enable it to spend more for economic and social sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
