<HEADLINE> Krajisnik Says Meeting With Plavsic Fails </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Momcilo Krajisnik, Serb
member of the Bosnian Presidency, said today his recent talk with
Bosnian Serb President Biljana Plavsic yielded no positive results
on resolving the current political crisis.
</P>
<P>
Krajisnik made the remarks in a statement in Bijeljina, the
Tanjug news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
During a four-hour secret meeting held Tuesday in Banja Luka,
Krajisnik suggested that Plavsic reverse "all illegal decisions"
and call the Bosnian Serb parliamentary and presidential elections
at the same time.
</P>
<P>
Plavsic rejected the suggestion, Tanjug said.
</P>
<P>
The crisis among the Bosnian Serb leadership began in early
July, when Plavsic dissolved the parliament despite strong
opposition from it.
</P>
<P>
The Constitutional Court ruled in August Plavsic's decision
unconstitutional, a ruling opposed by Plavsic.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Plavsic's exposure of high-level corruption led to
further conflict with Bosnian Serb hard-liners, who expelled her
from the Serb Social Democratic Party and called on her to resign
as president.
</P>
<P>
Plavsic insists that she would only step down if she was voted
out in a referendum, as required by the constitution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
