<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy, Spain Meet Over Single Currency, Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Italy and Spain today renewed
their resolve for a single European currency and stressed the role
of the European Union in reviving the stalled Middle East peace
talks in the first day of their annual summit.
</P>
<P>
Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi and his Spanish counterpart
Jose Maria Aznar "spoke with one voice in reiterating their firm
determination to respect the timetable and terms" of the single
currency, an Italian spokesman said after the premiers met in
Bologna, a central northern city of Italy.
</P>
<P>
Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini, who joined 15 other
ministers from the two countries at the meeting, said "Italy and
Spain think they will present the right scorecards" at the end of
April next year, when the first wave of countries to be in the
single currency, known as "Euro," will be decided.
</P>
<P>
Rodrigo Rato, Spain's deputy premier and minister for economy,
was quoted as saying by reports reaching here that Italy and Spain
were focusing on "working together for the future of the Euro."
</P>
<P>
To qualify for the single currency, countries must lower their
budget deficit to three percent of gross domestic product (GDP)
and their public debt to 60 percent of GDP. Their inflation rates
are also not to be more than 1.5 percentage point higher than the
average figure of the three best performing countries.
</P>
<P>
Though viewed as two countries having more difficulties in
meeting the criteria, Italy and Spain have managed to bring down
their deficit and inflation through austerity policies and fiscal
reforms.
</P>
<P>
Italy's deficit-GDP ratio, estimated to stand at 3.2 percent by
the end of 1997, is expected to drop to 3 percent in 1998, the
Internation Monetary Fund said earlier. And its inflation was
lowered to 1.5 percent in August, the lowest since the Spring of
1969, said Italy's national statistics institute Istat.
</P>
<P>
On Spain's part, inflation in March dropped to 2.2 percent, the
lowest in 29 years; and its public deficit was projected by an EU
report to fall to 3 percent in 1997 from 4.4 percent in 1996 and
6.6 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Also high on the agenda of the two countries' summit is how to
revive the peace talks in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The two premiers agreed the first step now is to bring Israel
and Palestinians back to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
They also said their own countries and the European Union as a
whole should play a role in restarting the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The 15-member EU will send its special envoy Miguel Angel
Moratinos to the Middle East after U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright's first mission to the region.
</P>
<P>
The two countries today also signed a principle accord to set
up a new joint force for peacekeeping and relief aid missions.
The new force would be the third such international body alongside
a United States force and a joint Anglo-Dutch one. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Current Account Surplus Soars in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Japan's current account surplus
in July rose 62.7 percent from a year earlier to 906 billion yen
(7.9 billion U.S. dollars), marking the fourth consecutive monthly
year-on-year increase, the Finance Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
The ministry attributed the rise to the yen's depreciation
against the dollar and favorable economic situation abroad,
particularly in the United States and Europe, which boosted
Japan's exports of automobiles and office equipment, including
personal computers.
</P>
<P>
In goods and services trading in July, Japan registered a
surplus of 474.2 billion yen (4.1 billion dollars), up 421.6
percent from a year before, the ministry said in a preliminary
report.
</P>
<P>
The surplus in merchandise trade surged 50.5 percent to 1,042.8
billion yen (9.1 billion dollars), up for the fourth straight
month.
</P>
<P>
Exports expanded 12.1 percent to 4,165.1 billion yen (36.2
billion dollars), up for the 24th consecutive month, while imports
edged up 3.3 percent to 3,122.3 billion yen (27.1 billion
dollars), rising for the 36th month in a row, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
In service trade, including tourism, Japan posted a deficit of
568.6 billion yen (4.9 billion dollars), down from a deficit of
601.9 billion yen (5.2 billion dollars) a year earlier, due partly
to a rise in the number of foreign tourists visiting Japan, the
ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The current account balance measures the flow of goods and
services as well as investment and other monetary transfers.
</P>
<P>
The ministry believes that the surplus is unlikely to continue
increasing in long term in view of ongoing changes in Japan's
economic structure.
</P>
<P>
Economists at private research institutions here, however,
forecast the surplus will continue to expand for the time being.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
