<HEADLINE> Taliban Said to Retreat From Afghan City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Afghan Taliban forces have
been pushed back by opposition forces from Mazar-e-Sharif, around
300 kilometers north of Kabul, amid reports that the student
militia also retreated from the newly-captured airport of the
city.
</P>
<P>
U.N. sources and foreign aid workers confirmed that the
anti-Taliban alliance forces were in full control of both
Mazar-e-Sharif, stronghold of Uzbek warlord Abdul Malik, and the
city's airport, the local newspaper The Muslim reported today.
</P>
<P>
Independent Afghan sources here said Wednesday evening that
Taliban fighters have finally retreated about 20 kilometers from
Afghanistan's second largest city after three days of fierce
fighting, The Muslim said.
</P>
<P>
However, the fear of an all-out offensive on Mazar-e-Sharif
still prevails as the Taliban are not far away from the city, the
Afghan sources said.
</P>
<P>
Taliban Interior Minister Khairullah Khairkhwa on Wednesday
claimed their forces were in control of Mazar-e-Sharif airport,
about eight kilometers east of the city.
</P>
<P>
He also requested the workers of the United Nations and foreign
non-governmental organizations to evacuate the city at the
earliest as the Taliban were all set for a decisive attack on
Mazar-e-Sharif, the only major Afghan city not in the Taliban's
hand.
</P>
<P>
Malik, who took control of Mazar-e-Sharif late May after
turning against his former boss Rashid Dostum, briefly sided with
the Taliban, allowing them into northern Afghanistan unopposed.
But after only five days, in a dispute over power-sharing, he
drove the Islamic militia out again.
</P>
<P>
Malik is supported by forces led by Afghanistan's former
military chief Ahmad Masood and Shiite group Hezb-e-Wadhat. Masood
has been battling the Taliban north of Kabul over the past two
months.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, which now control about two-thirds of
Afghanistan's territory and the capital of Kabul, have vowed to
impose strict Islamic rule in the war-torn country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
