<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Six Die on Indian Capital's Road Every Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 11 (Xinhua) -- With an average of about
six road deaths every day, New Delhi, capital of India, records
the highest number of accidents every year in the country, the
Hindustan Times said today.
</P>
<P>
The most vulnerable are the pedestrians and cyclists. This year
till August 31, 508 pedestrians were killed and 2,062 others
injured in road mishaps in the capital, the paper quoted the Delhi
Traffic Police as saying.
</P>
<P>
Heavy goods vehicles and Bluelines buses are said to be the
main culprits, followed by cars.
</P>
<P>
According to a study by the Central Road Research Institute,
trucks and buses are responsible for 43 percent of the accidents
in India.
</P>
<P>
Poor planning of roads is blamed as one of the main reasons for
the high rate of accidents in the capital.
</P>
<P>
There are 2.8 million cycles and cycle-rickshaws on the Delhi
road as against 2.7 million motorized vehicles. However, the roads
have been planned entirely for the motorized vehicles and no
consideration was given to the non-motorized and slow-moving
vehicles.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
