<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TIM's Profits UP 39 Percent in First Half of 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The mobile phone division of
Italian public Telecom Italia (TIM) reported net profits of 615
billion lire (347 million U.S. dollars) for the first half of the
year, compared with 440 billion lire (249 million dollars) for the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
While net profits rose 39.7 percent, revenues climbed 29.3
percent, to 4,338 trillion lire (2.45 billion dollars) from
January to the end of June this year.
</P>
<P>
The mid-year report approved by the board today also disclosed
that as of August 31, the number of TIM customers grew by 1.26
million over the first six months to a total of 7.7 million.
</P>
<P>
A communique issued by TIM said the mobile phone company's
common shares have risen in value by 41.14 percent since the
beginning of the year, compared with average gains of 27.3 percent
posted by the 30 most heavily capitalized shares listed on the
Milan Bourse, as shown on the Mib-30 index.
</P>
<P>
TIM also reported that the public mobile phone operator and
Omnitel, the Olivetti-led consortium which holds Italy's second
mobile phone franchise reached market penetration in Italy of 14.4
percent with more than 8.2 million customers. This compares with
12.6 percent in Britain with 7.3 customers shared by four
operators.
</P>
<P>
TIM's technical investments in the period rose 10 percent to
484 billion lire (273 million dollars). Two thirds of this figure
was earmarked for boosting the TACS networks, which now covers 75
percent of national territory and 96 percent of the population,
and GSM networks, now covering 69 percent of Italy's territory and
95 percent of the population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
