<HEADLINE> Milosevic Meets Int'l Official on Bosnian Serb Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic today told a top international official that the
international community should not take side in the Bosnian Serb's
 recent crisis.
</P>
<P>
Only by political means and through elections, Milosevic was
quoted as saying here by Yugoslav news media reports, could the
political crisis in the Bosnian Serb Republic be resolved.
</P>
<P>
The remarks were made during the Yugoslav leader's talks with
Carlos Westerndorp, the International High Representative for
Bosnia assigned to help implement the Dayton peace accord.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the escalating confrontations between those
with the Bosnian Serb parliament based in Pale and others loyal to
Bosnian Serb President Biljana Plavsic in Banja Luka.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference earlier in the day, Plavsic alleged that
her foes, labeled as hardliners, were attempting to stage a coup
before the elections scheduled for this weekend.
</P>
<P>
However, Milosevic told Westerndorp that the cracks among the
Serb leaders didn't mean they held different views on going ahead
with the Dayton accord on peace for Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he said, international forces should not be siding
with either side of the two parties.
</P>
<P>
Westerndorp talked to the press after the meeting that he and
Milosevic also discussed, among others, the restructuring of the
Serb Republic's police force.
</P>
<P>
Momcilo Krajisnik, the Serb member of Bosnia's tri-partite
presidency, was present at the meeting, as was Westerndorp's
deputy Jacques Klein. 
</P>
</TEXT>
