<HEADLINE> Uruguay Opposes Arms Sales to Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Uruguayan Foreign Minister
Alvaro Ramos today reiterated his country`s opposition to weapons
sales to Latin American countries.
</P>
<P>
"We disapprove of starting an armaments race in the
hemisphere," said Ramos. He was commenting on a decision taken by
the United States last month to lift the high-tech armament
embargo on Latin America.
</P>
<P>
This decision, announced by U.S. president Bill Clinton, raised
concern over a possible armaments race which would bring disaster
to the continent.
</P>
<P>
Chile was the first Latin American country to say it wanted to
buy modern airships to renew its air force, a fact that worried
its neighbors including Argentina, Bolivia and Peru.
</P>
<P>
"We have turned a confrontation scene into a cooperation one,"
underlined Ramos who completed a three-day visit to Costa Rica
today.
</P>
<P>
During talks between Ramos and Costa Rican Foreign Minister
Fernando Narajo, Narajo said he was also worried about the
U.S. decision.
</P>
<P>
"What we should really fear most is the beginning of an
armaments race," Narajo said. "Weapons purchases hurt investments
in development." 
</P>
</TEXT>
