<HEADLINE> 15 Dolphins Dead off Uruguayan Coasts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, September 10 (Xinhua) -- A total of 15 dead adult
dolphins were washed ashore in Uruguay's coastal departments of
Colonia and Canelones in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
The marine mammals suffered no hemorrhages or inner
wounds. Experts from the National Institute of Fishery are
investigating what caused the dolphins' death.
</P>
<P>
The dolphins, measuring 2.5 meters and weighing over 100
kilograms, usually live in groups in warm and salty waters between
30 degrees northern latitude and 30 degrees southern latitude near
the Atlantic coasts of the American continent.
</P>
<P>
Uruguayan scientists said the animals could be following a warm
stream flowing into Uruguayan, which is in winter, but they died
when entering low-temperature waters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
