<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Urges Cypriot Rivals to Reconcile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Italy fully supports the
European Union's position on the Cyprus issue, which recognizes
one government and two distinct communities in the country,
Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini said today.
</P>
<P>
During the talks with his Cypriot counterpart Loannis
Kasoulides who was visiting Italy, Dini said negotiations between
Greek and Turkish Cypriots on solving the dispute should
presuppose the peaceful coexistence between the two sides in a
single state.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey sent troops
to the island country and took over one third of its territory in
the wake of a failed coup there seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations and international community have been
working for decades to reunite the divided island, but so far no
concrete results have been achieved.
</P>
<P>
Now the Greek-Cypriot-dominated government in the southern part
of the island is recognized by most countries in the world.
</P>
<P>
Dini said that the key to the final solution to the protracted
Cyprus dispute is in the hands of the Greek and Turkish Cypriots
themselves.
</P>
<P>
The two sides of the divided Cyprus should make joint efforts
to dispel prejudices and hostility and promote mutual trust and
understanding, he added.
</P>
<P>
On the Cyprus' future membership of the EU, Dini reiterated
that Italy supports the island country in its efforts to join the
EU.
</P>
<P>
However, the Italian foreign minister said that in view of
the fact that there exist two distinct entities in the country, it
is unrealistic for the EU to accept Cyprus now.
</P>
<P>
Dini advised that the Greek and Turkish Cypriots make full use
of the country's application for the EU membership to promote the
process of reunification by holding concrete negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Any breakthrough in these peace negotiations could serve as
incentives to the acceptance of Cyprus by the EU, he added.
</P>
<P>
It was important for both the inter-community talks in Cyprus
and the talks between the island and the EU to progress
simultaneously, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Dini stressed the importance of Turkish Cypriots'
representation at the talks between Cyprus and the EU.
</P>
<P>
The visiting Cypriot foreign minister also met with Italian
Prime Minister Romano Prodi this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said that Italy was confident about the holding of the
Cyprus-EU talks in early 1998.
</P>
<P>
Prodi also called for a resumption of talks between Greek and
Turkish Cypriots under the aegis of U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot President Glafoks Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader
Rauf Denktas met last month in Switzerland under the U.N.
sponsorship, but no progress was made. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0269 </DOCNO>
