<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Urged to Boost Finance Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has urged
Thailand to strengthen the management of its finance sector while
pinpointing key areas that the country should tackle to revive the
sector.
</P>
<P>
The bank said Thailand's rules governing companies were weak
and its financial information lacked accuracy, timeliness and
transparency, according to The Bangkok Post today.
</P>
<P>
Thailand should set up a government unit to provide guidelines
for its financial institutions, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The country also should improve the supervision and appraisal
of its financial institutions while upgrading the quality of
economic information, it stressed.
</P>
<P>
The bank recommended that Thailand strengthen its laws on
bankruptcy and foreclosure of credit contracts by improving the
scope for loan recovery and debt restructuring.
</P>
<P>
It also suggested that the country strengthen its foreign-debt
and exchange risk management to achieve a safe and orderly
development of its finance sector.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the bank called for immediate re-checking on the
value of assets and liabilities of the ailing financial
institutions and their potential for auction.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank also cautioned that if the economic downturn
worsened because of the weakness in the property market, high
domestic interest rates and the fall in the exchange rate, it will
become more important for Thailand to improve its capacity to
identify risky and troubled institutions.
</P>
<P>
Early detection will limit the risk of weak institutions, it
noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0271 </DOCNO>
