<HEADLINE> Stone-Age Tribe Found in Irian Jaya, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- A stone-age tribe has been
discovered in the northern coastal plains of Yapen Waropen in the
shadow of the Van Rees mountains in Indonesia's easternmost
province of Irian Jaya, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
"The tribe, estimated to comprise 500 families, live in four
areas: Bonoi, Tamakuri, Koweda and Waren," Father T. J. Yoteni, a
local official, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
They are a nomadic tribe that lives from the land so they are
difficult to be reached by the government, he said.
</P>
<P>
The official called on all parties, both national and
provincial, especially the church, to help these people who are
still living in the Stone Age.
</P>
<P>
A Protestant church has already asked 35 preachers to live in
the area to teach these people religion and farming techniques, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Yoteni said they still do not know if the tribe can speak
Indonesian because it is difficult to reach these people.
</P>
<P>
No other details were given by the official about the tribe.
</P>
</TEXT>
