<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tung: Good Sino-U.S. Ties Helps Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The best way for the
United States to help Hong Kong is to develop good relations with
China, Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region, said here today.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference, Tung implied that it was wrong for some
United States congressmen to propose bills on elections in Hong
Kong. He advised: "The best way for America to help Hong Kong
is really to improve its relationship with China.
</P>
<P>
"A good and constructive relationship (between the U.S. and
China) will really help Hong Kong a lot as we move forward into
the 21st Century," Tung affirmed.
</P>
<P>
He hoped the visit by Chinese President Jiang Zemin in October
would be successful. "I believe he will have a good visit."
</P>
<P>
During his meetings with U.S. legislators, Tung, 60, told
reporters that he explained to the congressmen the transition of
Hong Kong and elections to be held next year.
</P>
<P>
"It is (for us) in Hong Kong to decide what is important, what
is right," said Tung. He was speaking after a second day of
meetings with U.S. congressmen.
</P>
<P>
"Most of our friends...appreciate and understand how well the
transition has gone, ...how confident we are about the future of
Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
Tung admitted that some congressmen "don't quite understand"
the issues in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Tung stressed that next year's legislative election will be
held in accordance with Hong Kong Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
"This is a good way to do it. It's a gradual, step-by-step
approach and I think it suits Hong Kong very well," he added.
</P>
<P>
Asked if he feels embarrassed by a bill on democracy in Hong
Kong advanced by Chairman Jesse Helms of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee on Monday, Tung replied, "No."
</P>
<P>
"That is because...we in Hong Kong care very much about
democracy. Democracy is not the monopoly of the United States of
America, or any western nations," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But we go forward in our own way that is right for Hong Kong,"
Tung declared.
</P>
<P>
Tung, who arrived here on Monday for a five-day visit to the
U.S., travelled to New York tonight and will return on Friday for
a meeting with President Bill Clinton at the White House. 
</P>
</TEXT>
