<HEADLINE> Italian FM Stresses Need to Revive Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister
Lamberto Dini today stressed the need to revive the Middle East
peace process after talks with visiting Saudi deputy premier and
defense minister.
</P>
<P>
Dini reiterated to Prince Sultan Ibn Abdul Aziz Al Saud the
need to "rebuild a correct negotiating climate" between the
Israelis and Palestinians after a recent wave of suicide bombings.
</P>
<P>
"A new start for the peace process is needed, and in particular
a strong commitment by all in the fight against terrorism, to
avert the risk that forces contrary to peace may win out," Dini
said.
</P>
<P>
He assured Prince Sultan that Italy and the European Union will
continue to work toward a resumption of peace talks, "in close
liaison with the United States."
</P>
<P>
Dini had just visited Washington where he voiced Italy's full
support for U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's first
Middle East mission this week.
</P>
<P>
He also said Saudi Arabia can do a lot to revive the Middle
East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia could "encourage a climate of moderation and the
resumption of talks" between Israelis and Palestinians, he said.
</P>
<P>
Prince Sultan, who last night met Italian Premier Romano Prodi,
concluded his Italian engagements today with talks with Italian
President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro, Interior Minister Giorgio
Napolitano and Defense Minister Beniamino Andreatta.
</P>
<P>
In the later talks, Andreatta and his Saudi counterpart
completed a deal to sell 22 Agusta helicopters to the Saudis and
agreed to hold joint land, naval and air exercises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
