<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Gorge Project Helps Curb Greenhouse Effect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Chinese environment protection
experts believe that the Three Gorges hydro-electric project will
help curb the global greenhouse effect and contribute to
environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
The project is the world's largest, with an installed capacity
of 18.2 million kilowatts and annual generating capacity of 84.7
billion kilowatt hours. It is expected to ease the power supply
shortage in eastern, central, and parts of southwestern China.
</P>
<P>
Lu Youmei, general manager of the Yangtze River Three Gorges
Development Corporation cited an impact analysis by Chinese
experts as saying that if it were replaced by coal-fired power
facilities, ten 1.8-million-kw stations would need to be built.
</P>
<P>
And, in addition to waste water and gas, more than 100 million
tons of carbon dioxide that could contribute to the global
greenhouse effect would be discharged annually from the coal-fired
stations, and more than 2 million tons of sulfur dioxide that
could cause acid rain.
</P>
<P>
Lu said that Chinese experts believe that the ecological
effects of the Three Gorges project, like silt and the impact on
rare plants and animals, can be solved by specific measures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
