<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Economy Expected to Slow Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's economic growth
would slow down this year but is likely to pick up in 1998 as the
currency crisis was only temporary, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
State Minister of National Development Planning Ginandjar
Kartasasmita said last night that Indonesia's economic growth also
slowed down in the early 1990s due to a tight monetary policy. But
after the monetary policy was eased, growth rebounded in the
subsequent years.
</P>
<P>
"This economic growth slow down will be temporary. Next year
will see robust growth again," the local press quoted the minister
as saying at a seminar.
</P>
<P>
A lower growth rate this year was due to the government's tight
monetary policy and the postponement and rescheduling of large
government projects aimed at preventing the currency crisis from
worsening into an economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
"We should not pursue high growth at the expense of other
important things," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Foreign Minister Ali Alatas said the country's
economic growth this year would slow down to about 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
"But it may not be that bad, it may only go down to 6 percent,"
he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Coordinating Minister for Economy and Finance Saleh Afiff said
earlier that growth could fall to about 5 percent if the currency
crisis continued.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's economic growth fell below 7 percent in 1992 and
1993 following the tight monetary policy. But growth picked up in
the following years, reaching 7.5 percent in 1994, 8.2 percent in
1995 and 7.8 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to prevent the currency crisis from worsening into an
economic crisis, the government moved last week to revise its
budget, liberalize foreign purchase of local shares and strengthen
the banking industry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
