<HEADLINE> Major Chinese Brewery Diversifies Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Wuliangye Brewery in Yibin
city of southwest China's Sichuan province, believed to be China's
largest brewery, has projected to make the plant a well-known
transnational corporation.
</P>
<P>
According to an expansion plan of the Brewery, the plant is to
invest one billion yuan anually in the coming 7 years to diversify
its production and develop highly value-added products and other
commodities related to the brewery industry.
</P>
<P>
The brewery's annual pretax profit is expected to reach 10
billion yuan by 2004 after the completion of the expansion plan,
Wang Guochun, director of the Wuliangye Brewery has said.
</P>
<P>
Wuliangye Brewery produced 100,000 tons of white spirits in
1996, with pretax profits for the year reaching 750 million
yuan.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Wuliangye has established a joint venture with
a British partner. It has also invested in four projects in Germany
and the United States.  
</P>
</TEXT>
