<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai PM Rules Out Dissolution of Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh has promised that he will not resign or dissolve the
House of Representatives before the passage of the new
constitution.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to a group of supporters from the provinces on
Wednesday, he said the opposition will not succeed in making him
dissolve the House or resign.
</P>
<P>
He said if he did that, it would be tantamount to destroying
the country and ruining its prospects.
</P>
<P>
He said that after the promulgation of the new constitution,
the draft of which is to be put to vote at the National Assembly
on September 27, he would push for passage of organic laws within
240 days, as required by the new charter.
</P>
<P>
He also said he was ready for the censure debate scheduled for
September 24 and 25.
</P>
<P>
Some opposition MPs have urged Chavalit to resign for
mismanagement of the economy. Others fear that the prime minister
might dissolve the House during the 15 days leading up to the vote
of the charter to delay its passage.
</P>
<P>
There are a number of clauses in the constitution draft which
are contentious and unacceptable to many politicians.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Rupiah, Stocks Follow on Regional Weakness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian rupiah and
stock prices declined Wednesday following general weakness in the
region, dealers and stock brokers said here today.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah was moving in tandem with its counterparts in the
region, with spot rupiah closing at 2,935/38 against the U.S.
dollar from an opening of 2,900/15 after two days of stability at
the 2,900 level.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said general weakness in regional currencies had
affected the rupiah, which even touched its lowest level at 2,944
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, stock prices in the Jakarta Stock Exchange dropped
3.84 percent, with the Composite Index falling 22.988 points to
close at 576.016.
</P>
<P>
Stock analysts said the drop was driven by continuing local-led
selling of blue chips amid generally weak regional markets.
</P>
<P>
"The central bank's interest rate cut appeared to have been
factored in," an analyst said. "Players took profit as they
expected few strong positive surprises in the short term."
</P>
<P>
The central bank cut interest rates on Tuesday for bilateral
central bank certificates (SBI) by between one and two percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
The move was taken as a follow-up to the government's reform
package announced on September 3 to relax the tight monetary
policy in stages.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has fallen more than 10 percent in the past month
and nearly 23 percent since January this year following offshore
speculative attacks on the currency and a rush by local companies
to hedge their foreign borrowings.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
