<HEADLINE> Poland Establishes New Special Economic Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Poland today opened a new
special economic zone in the southern city of Tarnobrzeg to
attract more foreign investment and boost employment there.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Wlodzimierz Cimoszewicz, who attended the
foundation stone laying ceremony, said Poland will establish at
least 15 special economic zones.
</P>
<P>
The country's first SEZ was set up in November 1995 in Mielec
following the promulgation in October the previous year of a law
on special economic zones.
</P>
<P>
The law stipulates that enterprises' with investment exceeding
2 million ECU (about 2.17 million U.S. dollars) or employing more
than 100 people can have their income tax exempted in the first 10
years and halved in the next 10 years. No alcohol, tobacco
enterprises and casinos are allowed in the zones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
