<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Myanmar Strives for Better Transportation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is trying to improve
its road, railroad, water and air transportation in an effort to
step up national and regional economic development.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, 4,363 kilometers of roads
have been added since 1988, extending their total length from
23,317 to 27,680 kilometers in the country.
</P>
<P>
Bridges, big and small, have been built to ensure better
transportation and their number has gone up from 4,932 to 5,078.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, six major bridges across Myanmar's mighty
Ayeyawaddy River have been under construction to cut the travel
time between its eastern and western banks. Major bridges are also
being built above the Thanlyin and Chindwin rivers.
</P>
<P>
Railroads were also extended in the country. With the addition
of 1,110 kilometers in the past nine years, their total length now
reaches 4,272 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has also imported modern railway machinery, equipment
and materials from countries including Germany and China to
upgrade its railway transportation services.
</P>
<P>
To better its inland water transportation, the country is
making efforts to acquire more and more boats for its fleet plying
along the country's major rivers.
</P>
<P>
With the addition of more than 100 passenger and cargo vessels
in the past nine years, Myanmar's inland water transport has
greatly improved.
</P>
<P>
In the 1996-97 fiscal year (April 96 to March 97), Myanmar's
Inland Water Transport Authorities provided transport services by
using 721 vessels.
</P>
<P>
The state-run Myanmar Five Star Line (MFSL), meanwhile, carried
out overseas and coastal shipping services with 23 vessels and it
is planning to obtain two more ocean-going multi-purpose vessels
from China to further boost its business.
</P>
<P>
The cooperative and private sectors have also been providing
inland and coastal transport services with a total of 4,440
vessels.
</P>
<P>
To promote freight transport, a new Myanmar international port
known as the Thilawa Port, together with 17 container wharves, is
being built with Singaporean, Malaysian and Italian-Thai
investments. At present, however, the Yangon Port is Myanmar's
main gateway to the world, handling all of its imports and more
than 90 percent of its exports.
</P>
<P>
The seaborne trade passing through the ports of Myanmar was 7
million tons in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
Air transport has also been improved in the country during the
past nine years with the establishment of joint-venture airlines
with foreign companies such as Air Mandalay and Yangon Airways
operating domestically and Myanmar Airways International flying to
seven destinations in the world.
</P>
<P>
To handle the increasing number of tourist arrivals and to
accommodate larger aircraft, two new international airports, one
in Mandalay and the other in Bago, are being built in addition to
the existing Yangon International Airport which has been renovated
and extended.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest official statistics, Myanmar's
transport sector achieved a growth rate of 4.5 percent in fiscal
1996-97 over the previous fiscal year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
