<HEADLINE> Austria Supports Ukraine's EU Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Austria is pledging to help
Ukraine with its pursuit of European Union (EU) membership,
visiting Austrian Vice Chancellor and Foreign Minister Wolfgang
Schussel said here today.
</P>
<P>
Schussel made the comment as the two countries plan to broaden
bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"Ukraine is widely viewed as a potent stabilizing factor in
Europe," said Schussel, who arrived here today on a one-day
working trip. "So Austria will keep supporting Ukraine's
integration with Europe."
</P>
<P>
He said Ukraine had scored two major successes internationally
-- the signing the special partnership charter with the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), and Ukraine's coming
presidency of the United Nations General Assembly's 52nd Session.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine regarded the Ukrainian-NATO partnership charter as an
important step closer to integration with Europe. "To obtain an EU
membership is a major goal of Ukraine's foreign policies,"
Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma told Schussel.
</P>
<P>
During Schussel's separate meetings with Ukrainian Prime
Minister Valeriy Pustovoitenko and Foreign Minister Gennady
Udovenko, hosts and guest voiced satisfaction over the development
of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Both sides hoped the annual trade volume between them would
shoot up to one billion U.S. dollars from the present 400 million
dollars. In the first half of 1997, Ukraine imported 91 million
dollars worth of commodities from Austria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
