<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Adopts High-tech in Fresco Preservation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, September 11 (Xinhua) -- China is using modern
computer technology to restore ancient frescoes in the Dunhuang
Caves on the Silk Road in Gansu province, northwest China.
</P>
<P>
Nuclear technology and X-rays are being used to study the
structure and composition of the pigments to find out why they
fade and change color.
</P>
<P>
After seceral years of study, new chemicals have been found for
renovating and preserving the valuable cultural heritage.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists are co-operating with Japanese and US
scientists to study environmental factors that damage the frescoes
by monitoring the air inside and outside the Dunhuang and Yungang
Caves.
</P>
<P>
Scientists have also successfully saved frescoes by removing
them and storing them elsewhere when needed. The largest
preservation center is in the Shaanxi History Museum, where a
large number of frescoes from the Tang Dynasty (seventh to tenth
century) have been kept.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
