<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shandong Province Establishes Modern Telecom Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, September 11 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province
has established a modern telecommunications network which features
program-controlled exchanges, digital transmissions, mobile and
paging communications, and teleconferencing facilities.
</P>
<P>
The handling capacity of public telephone exchanges in local
urban and rural areas approached 5.5 million lines by the end of
June, up seven-fold on figures for the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The province has more than 4.22 million telephone subscribers,
including 837,000 mobile phone users.
</P>
<P>
Shandong currently averages 6.59 telephones per 100 people, up
dramatically from 0.89:100 in 1990.
</P>
<P>
In addition to establishing a digital microwave communications
network in local areas, the province has exerted great effort to
introduce optical fibre trunk lines linked to neighboring
provinces. Related projects are part of an overall plan to improve
the local long-distance telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
The province has also installed satellite ground stations in
the coastal city of Weihai and the capital city of Jinan, in
addition to opening satellite telecom lines linking Weihai and
Seoul. China's second submerged optical fiber cable line provides
direct links to the Republic of Korea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
