<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More New Zealanders Rely on Welfare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- nearly one in every three
New Zealand adults is now receiving weekly welfare payments,
according to the latest figures released by the government.
</P>
<P>
The figures available today showed that the number of people
receiving benefits excluding superannuation rose 4 percent last
year to 367,000.
</P>
<P>
If pensioners are counted, the total will reach 826,000,
meaning almost one in three adults is on the dole.
</P>
<P>
Among the beneficiaries, 5 percent of the unemployed and 26
percent of the domestic purpose benefit (DPB) receivers have been
on the list for over five years.
</P>
<P>
Social Welfare Minister Roger Sowry was quoted by a press
report today as saying the scheme to help people move from welfare
to work by the Income Support Services would help stem the rise in
beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
He was particularly concerned about the high rate of growth of
people receiving an invalids benefit and his department is
reviewing it and the sickness benefit, "which will give us more
information to explain the reasons behind this rise."
</P>
<P>
But Patricia Schnauer, MP of the opposition ACT Party, blamed
the increase on welfare policy. "The DPB has created a huge
culture of dependency and single parenting evolving in this
country," she charged.  
</P>
</TEXT>
