<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0324 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl Optimistic about Punctual Start of Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 10 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl
today said he was optimistic that the planned single European
currency, the Euro, would be introduced punctually on January 1,
1999.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a parliament debate on Wednesday, Kohl stressed
that his government would do its best to ensure that the Euro
would be launched at the agreed time and be a stable currency in
the long run.
</P>
<P>
"We want both: a stable currency and the Euro at the right
time. We have a good chance to achieve this," Kohl said.
</P>
<P>
Although he admitted that many Germans were still reluctant to
give up their rock-hard German mark for a still uncertain common
currency, Kohl stressed that there was no alternative to such an
option.
</P>
<P>
"The vast majority of Germans have long realized that the
welfare and peaceful future of our nation are linked to the single
currency and the European Union," he said.
</P>
<P>
Germany has stirred up controversies in European capitals
recently when Hans Tietmeyer, president of Germany's central bank,
said in a newspaper interview that a delay of the Euro would not
be "a disaster".
</P>
<P>
On top of that, Kurt Biedenkopf, premier of the German state of
Saxony, on Monday also made a concrete call for a five-year delay
for the Euro launch.
</P>
<P>
The Euro debate came amid rising doubts over whether key
countries in the E.U., including Germany and France, would be able
to meet the fiscal criteria this year to qualify for the Euro.
</P>
<P>
In his speech to the German parliament on Wednesday, German
Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel criticized the recent debate on the
future of the Euro as "irresponsible and very dangerous".
</P>
<P>
The Euro was important not only for employment and export, but
also for maintaining credibility, he said.
</P>
<P>
The common currency was also a key topic at Wednesday's talks
in Bonn between German Finance Minister Theo Waigel and
Luxembourg's Prime Minister Jean-Claude Juncker.
</P>
<P>
Both of them expressed confidence that Germany would be able to
reduce its budget deficit this year to less than three percent of
gross domestic product in order to make the grade to join the
Euro.
</P>
<P>
"Contrary to the majority of the German public, I have never
doubt it," Juncker said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0325 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> (rpt with correction)German First-Half Deficit Within </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Germany achieved a deficit of
3.1 percent of gross domestic product (GDP) in the first half of
this year, within reach of meeting the criteria for joining the
single European currency, the euro, the Wiesbaden-based Federal
Statistics Office reported today.
</P>
<P>
European Union (E.U.) member states are required to keep
deficit under 3.0 percent of GDP for membership of the euro.
Germany has failed to meet the criteria over recent years. In
1996, its revised deficit stood at 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics office, the state spending in the
first half dropped by 0.9 percent while revenues rose by 1.4
percent. As a result, deficit increased by 54.3 billion marks
(30.6 billion U.S. dollars), 3.3 billion marks lower than in the
first half of 1996.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the country's economic performance improved,
registering a real 2.0 percent growth, which contributed to
bringing down the deficit-to-GDP ratio.
</P>
<P>
The office also noted that it used the E.U. statistical
compilation methods in calculating the state deficit this time,
which excludes public hospitals, as opposed to its previous
practices. Adopting E.U. method could improve Germany's
deficit-to-GDP ratio by 0.1 to 0.2 percentage points for 1997, it
said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the deficit data, Peter Pietsch, chief economist
at Commerzbank, said: "We are now more firmly convinced that
Germany will achieve the deficit criteria."
</P>
<P>
The euro is due to be launched on January 1, 1999. A E.U.
meeting early next year will decide which countries will then join
the single currency.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0326 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Money Worries Found to Be Growing in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Americans are plenty
worried about their money, especially since their wages have not
been keeping pace with inflation, a survey by Money magazine said
today.
</P>
<P>
Three out of five people surveyed said that they were satisfied
with their financial situation. But the same amount said they were
worried about the future -- the highest level of concern since
1993, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
As in the past, women are more jittery about money than men.
Fifty-four percent of women said an unexpected bill of 1,000
dollars would be a big problem for their household, while only 36
percent of men said they felt the same way.
</P>
<P>
"Although people are confident about how the economy is doing
and how they are doing personally, their optimism is guarded,"
said Adam Richard, senior vice president of Willard &AMP; Shullman,
which conducted the survey for the magazine.
</P>
<P>
The survey also found that Americans are running up more debt.
The average monthly household credit card bill rose by 5 percent
last year to 263 dollars, while baby boomers with no kids are
blowing almost 10 percent of their pay on monthly credit card
payments.
</P>
<P>
The survey was compiled from 1,120 written responses to a
12-page questionnaire sent to 4,500 randomly selected households
across the country in May and June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
