<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Economy Up 2.0 Percent in First Half </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Germany registered a real 2.0
percent increase in gross domestic product (GDP) in the first half
of this year, indicating that the country's economy was gaining
momentum, the Wiesbaden-based Federal Statistics Office reported
today.
</P>
<P>
In particular, the country's GDP grew by a real 2.9 percent in
the second quarter, the office noted.
</P>
<P>
The figures heighten the prospects for an officially-projected
2.5 percent growth rate this year. In 1996, Germany's economic
growth was 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the office, the economic pickup came as a result
of strong exports, which increased by a real 9.6 percent in the
first half. During the period, the country's private consumption
remained weak, rising just 0.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Welcoming the economic data, German Economics Minister Guenter
Rexrodt said that he expected the export boom would stimulate the
domestic business. As a sign of this, he added, capital equipment
investments in Germany grew by 3.6 percent in the first half.
</P>
</TEXT>
