<DOCNO> XIE19970911.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: EU Agricultural Reform Remains in Trouble </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The only result which the
European Union (EU)'s agriculture ministers achieved at an
informal meeting held lately in Luxembourg seemed to be letting
everybody concerned know that reform of the agricultural sector
would remain the most difficult issue in its integration process.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the three-day meeting, which closed Tuesday in
Echternach in Luxembourg, was to provide a forum for a full
exchange of views on further reform of the EU's Common
Agricultural Policy (CAP), which was launched in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, EU Agriculture Commissioner Franz Fischler had
wanted to take advantage of the meeting to gauge the extent of the
member states' opposition to the controversial Agenda 2000 reform
project which he has spent much time and energy promoting.
</P>
<P>
However, the outcome of this informal debate is of limited
significance though all the ministers agreed that now was the time
to embark upon the reform process and voiced unanimous support for
the fundamental objectives of the CAP reform drawn up by Fischler.
</P>
<P>
Much of the dissent expressed by the ministers focused on
specific aspects of the proposed reform, rather than its
overarching strategy.
</P>
<P>
Italy, while supportive of the general thrust of the proposed
reforms, was highly critical of the EU's current policy on beef
and milk.
</P>
<P>
Italian Agriculture Minister Michele Pinto said that the
current market organizations for these products favored intensive
farming models, therefore unsuited to Italian agriculture, which
is characterized by a far smaller average farm size.
</P>
<P>
He also agreed with Spain's Loyala de Palacio that the EU's
13-year-old milk quota should be urgently reviewed. Both ministers
described the proposed dairy market reforms set out in the July 15
package, which was launched by EU President Jacques Santer, as
inadequate.
</P>
<P>
They both expressed their support for a so-called "A/B" quota
system, whereby dairy farmers would be permitted to produce
unlimited quantities of milk for export, but would have to respect
strict quotas in producing for the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
Henrik Dam Kristensen, agriculture minister of Denmark,
criticized the proposed dairy reforms at the meeting, saying that
it was insufficiently radical.
</P>
<P>
He voiced his support for either a complete dismantling of the
current quota system, or an introduction of an A/B mechanism of
the kind favored by Italy and Spain.
</P>
<P>
But the most fundamental critique of the reform project seemed
to have stemmed from German Agriculture Minister Jorchen Borchet,
who said that much of the work undertaken since 1992, particularly
the severe cut-backs in the beef, cereals, oilseeds and dairy
sectors, should not be ignored and even questioned.
</P>
<P>
Describing the market analyses which underlie the Agenda 2000
reform project as "extraordinarily pessimistic", Borchet argued
that EU farmers would always be able to compete on world markets
by virtue of the high quality of their products.
</P>
<P>
The German minister protested at the cost of implementing the
European Commission's proposals, which he estimated at four
billion ECUs (some 5.2 billion U.S. dollars) per year.
</P>
<P>
In late 1980s, the EU's expenditure in the agricultural sector
neared 60 percent of its total budget. In 1996, the EU used almost
half of its spending to subsidize the agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
On its way towards the Economic and Monetary Union, Agenda 2000
was put forward to abolish prices support, reduce the prices of
agricultural products and make EU farmers focus more on quality
of their products.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the 1994 GATT agreement obliged the EU to
drastically cut back on its price subsidies and the new round of
talks on agriculture scheduled for 1999 will compel the EU to make
further concessions in this regard.
</P>
<P>
The EU was determined to reform its agricultural sector also
because it is preparing now to expand to Central and Eastern
European countries, some of which have comparatively higher
agricultural percentages in their gross national products.
</P>
<P>
Given that different EU countries have different agricultural
aspects and interests to think about, it seemed no easy task to
get even a "broad approval" for the agriculture chapter of Agenda
2000, which Luxembourg's Agriculture Minister Fernand Boden
however said he was optimistic about.
</P>
<P>
But he also indicated that the topic would be discussed at
every European Council session between now and the December
European Council, which analysts say signaled the hidden fear of
the EU ministers that the agricultural sector would remain a
thorny issue for quite a long time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
