<HEADLINE> U.S.: Beijing Talks with DPRK "Useful and Productive" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The State Department on
Wednesday called Beijing Talks between the United States and the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) "useful and
productive."
</P>
<P>
"Deputy Assistant Secretary of State Charles Kartman met
North Korea Vice Foreign Minister Kim Gye-gwan today in Beijing.
The meeting was useful and productive. It was conducted in a
professional manner," spokesman James Foley told reporters.
"They will meet again tomorrow to continue their discussion."
</P>
<P>
Foley declined to get into details of the talks, saying "no
concrete news yet on that issue."
</P>
<P>
It was the first meeting of senior U.S. and DPRK officials
since Washington granted political asylum to two DPRK diplomats
last month, which gave rise to tensions between the United
States and the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
Pyongyang has claimed the two defected diplomats, Chang
Sung-gil and his brother Chang Sung-ho, were criminals and asked
Washington to return the two defectors.
</P>
<P>
DPRK officials have since left unattended a meeting with
U.S. officials on missile discussions in New York.
</P>
<P>
The United States hoped that the DPRK would not relinquish
a preparatory meeting for four-party peace talks scheduled in
mid-September.
</P>
<P>
Foley told reporters that Pyongyang had given no "indication of
a falling back" from attending the four-party talks. 
</P>
