<HEADLINE> Egypt: Albright's Visit Not Confined to Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foregin Minister Amr
Moussa said here today that the agenda of U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright's first visit to the Middle East is not
confined to the security issue.
</P>
<P>
"We know that security is a key item on her agenda, but it is
not the only item," he told the press.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said that Egypt would examine with Albright various
dimensions of the regional situation.
</P>
<P>
Albright stressed after her talks today with Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Natanyahu that her three-day visit to Israel
would focus on the security issue.
</P>
<P>
However, she admitted that real security is inseparable with
real peace.
</P>
<P>
Asked on reported statement by American sources on a proposed
45-day halt of settlement construction in East Jerusalem's Jabal
Abu Gheneim, Moussa said it is not a matter of "halting" or
"postponing" construction, settlement building is in itself an
"illegal and illegitimate act."
</P>
<P>
Albright reportedly proposed following her arrival in Israel
today a 45-day freeze in Israel's settlement construction in
East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Albright will meet separately with Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian National Authority President
Yasser Arafat before going to Syria, Egypt, Jordan, Saudi Arabia
and probably Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the first Arab country to sign a peace treaty with
Israel, has been mediating between the Palestinian and Israeli
sides.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have been stalled since
March when Israel began building settlements in East Jerusalem.
The crisis is worsening following two rounds of suicide bombings
in West Jerusalem, killing 25 people and injuring more than 300
others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
