<HEADLINE> Lebanese PM Leaves for France for Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri left here tonight for France for a two-day visit aimed at
enhancing bilateral ties and discussing the Middle East Peace
process, Lebanese Orient Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
In France, Hariri will meet with French President Jacques
Chirac and Prime Minister Lionel Jospin, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
This will be Hariri's first meeting with his French
counterpart, who assumed office in last June.
</P>
<P>
There had been speculations that Lebanon would fall victim to
the tense relations between Chirac, Hariri's personal friend and
ally, and Jospin who ousted Lebanon's traditional right-wing
allies from power in the recent French elections.
</P>
<P>
In addition to signing a 1997 financial protocol, the radio
said that topping the agenda of the talks between the two
countries' leaders is the situation in the Middle East and south
Lebanon which is being occupied by Israeli troops.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon, which had been under France's mandate before its
independence in 1943, has been enjoying good relations with
France.
</P>
<P>
France, one of the major mediators in the Middle East peace
process, always supports Lebanon's demand that Israel
unconditionally withdraws from its occupied territory in south
Lebanon. 
</P>
