<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German First-Half Deficit Within Reach of Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Germany achieved a deficit of
3.1 percent of gross domestic product (GDP) in the first half of
this year, within reach of meeting the criteria for joining the
single European currency, the euro, the Wiesbaden-based Federal
Statistics Office reported today.
</P>
<P>
European Union (E.U.) member states are required to keep
deficit under 3.0 percent of GDP for membership of the euro.
Germany has failed to meet the criteria over recent years. In
1996, its deficit stood at 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics office, the state spending in the
first half dropped by 0.9 percent while revenues rose by 1.4
percent. As a result, deficit increased by 54.3 billion marks
(30.6 billion U.S. dollars), 3.3 billion marks lower than in the
first half of 1996.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the country's economic performance improved,
registering a real 2.0 percent growth, which contributed to
bringing down the deficit-to-GDP ratio.
</P>
<P>
The office also noted that it used the E.U. statistical
compilation methods in calculating the state deficit this time,
which excludes public hospitals, as opposed to its previous
practices. Adopting E.U. method could improve Germany's
deficit-to-GDP ratio by 0.1 to 0.2 percentage points for 1997, it
said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the deficit data, Peter Pietsch, chief economist
at Commerzbank, said: "We are now more firmly convinced that
Germany will achieve the deficit criteria."
</P>
<P>
The euro is due to be launched on January 1, 1999. A E.U.
meeting early next year will decide which countries will then join
the single currency.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
