<HEADLINE> Boeing Turns Out Longest Commercial Jet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Boeing rolled out the
world's longest jetliner, a stretched version of its new 777 at
its plant in Everett, Washington, today.
</P>
<P>
The new jet, modeled as 777-300, is 73.42 meters in length,
3.30 meters longer than Boeing's 747-400, the world's largest
commercial jet. With the ability to carry 550 passengers, the new
model is designed for high-capacity and medium-range routes.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the city said that Boeing has 50 orders for the
plane, all from Asian airlines, who plan to use it on such routes
as Tokyo-Singapore and Honolulu-Seoul.
</P>
<P>
Cathay Pacific, the largest airline in Hong Kong, has ordered
seven of the new planes. It will take delivery of the first
777-300 in May 1998 after Boeing completes a flight test program.
The plane is to make its first flight in mid-October.
</P>
<P>
Boeing delivered its first 777 in May 1995. The model 777-200
holds up to 328 passengers and can fly up to 13,160 kilometers.
The new plane, 10 meters longer than the earlier version, will
carry up to 394 passengers and up to 550 in all-economy
configurations, but with a range of 9,900 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Boeing, now producing about 30 jetliners
a month, plans to boost that rate to 43 planes a month by next
spring.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
