<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Committee Recommends Shelton to Head </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 10 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate Armed
Services Committee today unanimously recommended that the Senate
confirm Army Gen. Henry Shelton as Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff of the U.S. military.
</P>
<P>
The Committee's support for the current commander of America's
elite special operations troops came a day after he testified on
his nomination by President Bill Clinton to replace Army Gen. John
Shalikashvili, who is to retire by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
The Senate vote is expected to be held on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 55-year-old Shelton, who led U.S. forces in Haiti, would be
the third Army general in a row to fill a job that traditionally
has rotated among Army, Navy and Air Force officers.
</P>
<P>
At the hearing on Tuesday, Shelton promised to put the welfare
of troops in a shrinking post-Cold War military ahead of all
concerns and said he would continue a push to modernize U.S.
weaponry for the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
He also said he would support Clinton's plan to remove the U.S.
troops from Bosnia in mid-1998, and was opposed to using U.S.
peacekeeping troops to arrest indicted war criminals in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Shelton's nomination in July came weeks after Air Force Gen.
Joseph Ralston, vice chairman of the Joint Chiefs, withdrew from
the running after it was revealed he had had an adulterous affair
in the past. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
