<HEADLINE> Lugar: Helms Dictatorial on Weld's Nomination Hearing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September (Xinhua) -- Chairman Jesse Helms of the
U.S. Senate Foreign Relations Committee is being "arbitrary and
dictatorial" by refusing to hold a hearing on William Weld's
nomination as ambassador to Mexico, Senator Richard Lugar said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Lugar, a prominent Republican on the Committee, made the
accusation on the "Today" show of the National Broadcasting
Company (NBC).
</P>
<P>
"Clearly, he is quite arbitrary and dictatorial with regard to
this hearing," Lugar said. "He has indicated that something will
not occur regardless of who in the world might want to have it."
</P>
<P>
Helms, who bowed to bipartisan pressure Tuesday and called a
"special meeting" on Weld, still insisted that "the Weld
nomination will not be on the agenda."
</P>
<P>
Lugar and other members of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee proposed the meeting although they did not say whether
they will vote for the nomination or not.
</P>
<P>
The White House, who strongly backs the nomination, welcomed
Lugar's challenge to Helms, and questioned the fairness of
Friday's special meeting.
</P>
<P>
"That doesn't make sense to the White House. The whole notion
of a presidential nominee not getting a hearing doesn't make
sense," White House spokesman Mike McCurry said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
